* {{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = Morocco protest after raped Amina Filali kills herself | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-17379721 | work = [[BBC News]] | date = 15 March 2012 | accessdate = 19 November 2013}}</ref> In Lebanon, the [[Campaign Against Lebanese Rape Law - Article 522]] was launched in December 2016 to abolish the article that permitted a rapist to escape prison by marrying his victim.

Internationally, the incidence of rapes recorded by police during 2008 varied between 0.1 per 100,000 people in [[Egypt]] and 91.6 per 100,000 people in [[Lesotho]] with 4.9 per 100,000 people in [[Lithuania]] as the [[median]].<ref name="unodc1">{{cite book | last = UNODC | author-link = United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime | title = Rape at the National Level, number of police recorded offenses | url = http://www.unodc.org/documents/data-and-analysis/Crime-statistics/Sexual_violence_sv_against_children_and_rape.xls | format = spreadsheet | publisher = [[United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime]] }}</ref> In some countries, rape is not reported or properly recorded by police because of the consequences on the victim and the stigma attached to it.

===Marital rape===
{{Main|Marital rape|domestic violence}}
Marital or spousal rape was once widely condoned or ignored by law, and is now widely considered an unacceptable violence against women and repudiated by international conventions and increasingly criminalized. Still, in many countries, spousal rape either remains legal, or is illegal but widely tolerated and accepted as a husband's prerogative. The criminalization of spousal rape is recent, having occurred during the past few decades. Traditional understanding and views of [[marriage]], [[rape]], [[sexuality]], [[gender roles]] and [[self determination]] have started to be challenged in most Western countries during the 1960s and 1970s, which has led to the subsequent criminalization of marital rape during the following decades. With a few notable exceptions, it was during the past 30 years when most laws against marital rape have been enacted. Some countries in Scandinavia and in the former Communist Bloc of Europe made spousal rape illegal before 1970, but most Western countries criminalized it only in the 1980s and 1990s. In many parts of the world the laws against marital rape are very new, having been enacted in the 2000s.

In [[Canada]], marital rape was made illegal in 1983, when several legal changes were made, including changing the rape statute to ''sexual assault'', and making the laws gender neutral.<ref name=grady>{{cite book | last = Grady | first = William | title = Crime in Canadian context: debates and controversies | publisher = Oxford University Press | location = Don Mills, Ontario | year = 2011 | isbn = 9780195433784 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last1 = Brennan | first1 = Shannon| last2 = Taylor-Butts | first2 = Andrea | title = Sexual assault in Canada, 2004 | publisher = Canadian Centre for Justice Statistics | location = Ottawa | year = 2008 |url=http://www.statcan.gc.ca/pub/85f0033m/85f0033m2008019-eng.pdf | isbn = 9781100111636 |accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last = SIECCAN |title=Sexual assault in Canada: what do we know? |publisher=The Sex Information and Education Council of Canada (SIECCAN) | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140722071229/http://sexualityandu.ca/uploads/files/SexualAssault-OCT2011-ENG.pdf | archive-date = 22 July 2014 |url=http://sexualityandu.ca/uploads/files/SexualAssault-OCT2011-ENG.pdf | date = October 2011 |accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref> In [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]] spousal rape was outlawed in 1990.<ref name="Temkin86">{{cite book | last = Temkin | first = Jennifer | chapter = Defining and redefining rape | editor-last = Temkin | editor-first = Jennifer | title = Rape and the legal process | page = 86 | publisher = Oxford University Press | location = Oxford New York | year = 2002 | edition = 2nd | isbn = 9780198763543 }}
:''Citing'':
:* {{cite web | title = Criminal Law (Rape) (Amendment) Act, 1990, section 5 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170429001010/http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1990/act/32/section/5/enacted/en/html#sec5 | archive-date = 29 April 2017 | url = http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1990/act/32/section/5/enacted/en/html#sec5 | website = irishstatutebook.ie | publisher = [[Irish Statute Book]] | access-date = 21 December 2017}}</ref> In the US, the criminalization of marital rape started in the mid-1970s and in 1993 North Carolina became the last state to make marital rape illegal.<ref>{{cite news|last =Associated Press|author-link=Associated Press|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1957&dat=19930702&id=_xYxAAAAIBAJ&pg=6288,228462 |title=N.C. the last state to outlaw marital rape |work=[[The Daily Gazette]]| location = New York |date=2 July 1993 |accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref>
In [[England and Wales]], marital rape was made illegal in 1991. The views of Sir Matthew Hale, a 17th-century jurist, published in ''The History of the Pleas of the Crown'' (1736), stated that a husband cannot be guilty of the rape of his wife because the wife "hath given up herself in this kind to her husband, which she cannot retract"; in England and Wales this would remain law for more than 250 years, until it was abolished by the [[Appellate Committee of the House of Lords]], in the case of ''R v R'' in 1991.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bailii.org/uk/cases/UKHL/1991/12.html |title=R v R [1991&#93; UKHL 12 (23 October 1991) |publisher=British and Irish Legal Information Institute |accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref> In the [[Netherlands]] marital rape was also made illegal in 1991.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Zeegers | first = Nicolle | title = What epistemology would serve criminal law best in finding the truth about rape? | journal = Law and Method | volume = 2 | issue = 1 | pages = 60&ndash;71 | date = January 2012 | ref = harv | doi = 10.5553/ReM/221225082012002001005 }} [https://www.bjutijdschriften.nl/tijdschrift/lawandmethod/2012/1/ReM_2212-2508_2012_002_001_005.pdf Pdf.]</ref> One of the last Western countries to criminalize marital rape was [[Germany]], in 1997.<ref>{{cite thesis|last=Kieler|first=Marita|date=2003|title=Tatbestandsprobleme der sexuellen Nötigung, Vergewaltigung sowie des sexuellen Mißbrauchs widerstandsunfähiger Personen|publisher=[[University of Osnabrück]] via Tenea|url=http://www.jurawelt.com/dissertationen/werke/8821|oclc=758907108}} [http://www.jurawelt.com/sunrise/media/mediafiles/13792/tenea_juraweltbd52_kieler.pdf Pdf.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020164804/http://www.jurawelt.com/sunrise/media/mediafiles/13792/tenea_juraweltbd52_kieler.pdf |date=20 October 2013 }}</ref>

The relation between some religions ([[Christianity]] and [[Islam]]) and marital rape is controversial. The [[Bible]] at 1 Corinthians 7:3-5 explains that one has a "conjugal duty" to have sexual relations with one's spouse (in sharp opposition to [[sex outside marriage]], which is considered a [[sin]]) and states, "The wife does not have authority over her own body, but the husband does. And likewise the husband does not have authority over his own body, but the wife does. Do not deprive one another..."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=1+corinthians%207:3-7:5&version=NKJV |title=1 corinthians 7:3-7:5 NKJV | website = biblegateway.com |publisher=[[BibleGateway.com|Bible Gateway]] |accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref> Some conservative religious figures interpret this as rejecting to possibility of marital rape.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.adn.com/2011/07/22/1980301/readers-blast-valley-paper-over.html |title=Valley paper criticized over pastor's column on spousal rape |work=[[Alaska Dispatch]] |date=22 July 2011 |accessdate=6 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029203959/http://www.adn.com/2011/07/22/1980301/readers-blast-valley-paper-over.html |archivedate=29 October 2013}}</ref> Islam makes reference to sexual relations in marriage too, notably: "Allah's Apostle said, 'If a husband calls his wife to his bed (i.e. to have sexual relation) and she refuses and causes him to sleep in anger, the angels will curse her till morning';"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sacred-texts.com/isl/bukhari/bh4/bh4_464.htm |title=Hadith 4:460 | website = Sacred-texts.com |publisher=[[Internet Sacred Text Archive]] |accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref> and several comments on the issue of marital rape made by Muslim religious leaders have been criticized.<ref>{{cite news| last = Halliday | first =Josh |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/nov/08/islam-channel-ofcom |title=Islam Channel censured by Ofcom |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=8 November 2010 |accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Staff writer| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/7843909.stm | work=[[BBC News]] | title=Cleric 'must deny' views on rape | date=22 January 2009 | access-date = 11 December 2013}}</ref>

===Domestic violence===
[[File:Anti-domestic violence sign in Liberia panoramio (193).jpg|thumb|Anti-domestic violence sign in [[Liberia]]]]
{{main|Domestic violence|Intimate partner violence}}
Women are more likely to be [[victimized]] by someone that they are intimate with, commonly called "[[intimate partner violence]]" (IPV). Instances of IPV tend not to be reported to police and thus many experts find it hard to estimate the true magnitude of the problem.<ref>{{cite web | title = Intimate partner violence: fact sheet | url = https://www.cdc.gov/ncipc/factsheets/ipvfacts.htm | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070211183916/http://www.cdc.gov/ncipc/factsheets/ipvfacts.htm | archive-date = 11 February 2007 | website = cdc.gov/ncipc | publisher = National Center for Injury Prevention and Control, [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] | date = 2006 | accessdate = 4 September 2007}}</ref> Though this form of violence is often considered as an issue within the context of heterosexual relationships, it also occurs in lesbian relationships,<ref>{{Cite journal | last = Girshick | first = Lori B. | title = No sugar, no spice: reflections on research on woman-to-woman sexual violence | journal = [[Violence Against Women (journal)|Violence Against Women]] | volume = 8 | issue = 12 | pages = 1500–1520 | publisher = [[Sage Publications|Sage]] | doi = 10.1177/107780102237967 | date = December 2002 | s2cid = 73280087 | ref = harv }}</ref> daughter-mother relationships, [[roommate]] relationships and other domestic relationships involving two women. Violence against women in lesbian relationships is about as common as violence against women in heterosexual relationships.<ref>{{cite web | last = Rose | first = Suzana | title = Lesbian partner violence fact sheet | url = http://www.musc.edu/vawprevention/lesbianrx/factsheet.shtml | publisher = [[Medical University of South Carolina]] }}</ref>

Women are much more likely than men to be [[murdered]] by an intimate partner. In the United States, in 2005, 1181 women were killed by their intimate partners, compared to 329 men.<ref>{{cite web | title = Intimate partner violence: consequences | url = https://www.cdc.gov/violencePrevention/intimatepartnerviolence/consequences.html | website = cdc.gov/ncipc | publisher = National Center for Injury Prevention and Control, [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] | accessdate = 9 February 2010 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100129161946/http://www.cdc.gov/violencePrevention/intimatepartnerviolence/consequences.html | archive-date = 29 January 2010 | url-status = dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Wheel gallery | url = http://www.theduluthmodel.org/wheelgallery.php | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110728093413/http://www.theduluthmodel.org/wheelgallery.php | archive-date = 28 July 2011 | publisher=The Duluth Model | accessdate = 9 February 2010}}</ref> In [[England and Wales]] about 100 women are killed by partners or former partners each year while 21 men were killed in 2010.<ref>{{cite news | last = Staff writer |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-13058300 |title=All domestic abuse deaths to have multi-agency review |date=13 April 2011 | work = BBC news |accessdate=14 April 2011}}</ref> In 2008, in [[France]], 156 women were killed by their intimate partner, compared to 27 men.<ref>{{cite book | title = L'action du ministère dans le cadre des violences au sein du couple / Aide aux victimes: présentation des différents dispositifs | url = http://www.interieur.gouv.fr/sections/a_votre_service/aide_aux_victimes/violence-couple/downloadFile/attachedFile/morts_violentes_au_sein_couples.pdf | language = French | publisher = [[Minister of the Interior (France)|Ministère de l'Intérieur]] | accessdate = 6 August 2014 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120320014223/http://www.interieur.gouv.fr/sections/a_votre_service/aide_aux_victimes/violence-couple/downloadFile/attachedFile/morts_violentes_au_sein_couples.pdf | archivedate = 20 March 2012}}</ref> According to the WHO, globally, as many as 38% of murders of women are committed by an intimate partner.<ref name="WHO VAM Factsheet" /> A UN report compiled from a number of different studies conducted in at least 71 countries found domestic violence against women to be most prevalent in [[Ethiopia]].<ref>{{cite news | title = Ethiopian women are most abused | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/6040180.stm | work = BBC News | date = 11 October 2006 }}</ref> A study by [[Pan American Health Organization]] conducted in 12 [[Latin American]] countries found the highest prevalence of domestic violence against women to be in [[Bolivia]].<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Bott | first1 = Sarah | last2 = Guedes | first2 = Alessandra | last3 = Goodwin | first3 = Mary | last4 = Mendoza | first4 = Jennifer Adams | title = Violence against women in Latin America and the Caribbean: a comparative analysis of population-based data from 12 countries | url = http://www.paho.org/Hq/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=8175%3A2013-violence-against-women-latin-america-caribbean-comparative-analysis&catid=1505%3Aabout-us&lang=en | publisher = [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] and the [[Pan American Health Organization]] | date = 2012 }} [http://www1.paho.org/hq/dmdocuments/violence-against-women-lac.pdf English pdf.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160204013306/http://www1.paho.org/hq/dmdocuments/violence-against-women-lac.pdf |date=4 February 2016 }} [http://www.paho.org/Hq/index.php?option=com_docman&task=doc_download&gid=24353&Itemid=270&lang=en Spanish pdf.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150408155433/http://www.paho.org/Hq/index.php?option=com_docman&task=doc_download&gid=24353&Itemid=270&lang=en |date=8 April 2015 }}</ref> In Western Europe, a country that has received major international criticism for the way it has dealt legally with the issue of violence against women is [[Finland]]; with authors pointing out that a high level of equality for women in the public sphere (as in Finland) should never be equated with equality in all other aspects of women's lives.<ref>{{Cite journal | last = Clarke | first = Kris | title = The paradoxical approach to intimate partner violence in Finland | journal = [[Tokiwa University#Publications|International Perspectives in Victimology]] | volume = 6 | issue = 1 | pages = 9–19 | publisher = [[Tokiwa University]] via [[California State University|The Press at California State University]] | doi = 10.5364/ipiv.6.1.19 | date = August 2011 | ref = harv | doi-broken-date = 20 November 2020 }} [https://www.academia.edu/992154/The_Paradoxical_Approach_to_Intimate_Partner_Violence_in_Finland Available through academia.edu.]</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=McKie |first1=Linda |last2=Hearn |first2=Jeff |title=Gender-neutrality and gender equality: comparing and contrasting policy responses to 'domestic violence' in Finland and Scotland |journal=[[Scottish Affairs]] |volume=48 |issue=1 |pages=85–107 |publisher=[[Edinburgh University Press]] |doi=10.3366/scot.2004.0043 |date=August 2004 |ref=harv }} [https://web.archive.org/web/20131021023708/http://www.scottishaffairs.org/backiss/pdfs/sa48/sa48_McKie_and_Hearn.pdf Pdf.]</ref><ref>{{cite report |date=September 2008 |title=Case Closed: Rape and Human Rights in the Nordic Countries |publisher=Amnesty International |url=https://amnesty.dk/media/1557/case-closed.pdf | pages = 89–91 | quote = Finland is repeatedly reminded of its widespread problem of violence against women and recommended to take more efficient measures to deal with the situation. International criticism concentrates on the lack of measures to combat violence against women in general and in particular on the lack of a national action plan to combat such violence and on the lack of legislation on domestic violence. (...) Compared to Sweden, Finland has been slower to reform legislation on violence against women. In Sweden, domestic violence was already illegal in 1864, while in Finland such violence was not outlawed until 1970, over a hundred years later. In Sweden the punishment of victims of incest was abolished in 1937, but not until 1971 in Finland. Rape within marriage was criminalised in Sweden in 1962, but the equivalent Finnish legislation only came into force in 1994 – making Finland one of the last European countries to criminalise marital rape. In addition, assaults taking place on private property did not become impeachable offences in Finland until 1995. Only in 1997 did victims of sexual offences and domestic violence in Finland become entitled to government-funded counselling and support services for the duration of their court cases. | ref = harv }}</ref>

====Diagnosis planning====
The [[American Psychiatric Association]] planning and research committees for the forthcoming [[DSM-5]] (2013) have canvassed a series of new [[Relational disorder]]s, which include ''Marital Conflict Disorder Without Violence'' or ''Marital Abuse Disorder (Marital Conflict Disorder With Violence)''.<ref name="Personality">{{cite book| last1 = First | first1 = Michael B. | last2 = Bell | first2 = Carl C. | last3 = Cuthbert | first3 = Bruce | last4 = Krystal | first4 = John H. | last5 = Malison | first5 = Robert | last6 = Offord | first6 = David R. | last7 = Reiss | first7 = David | last8 = Shea | first8 = M. Tracie | last9 = Widger | first9 = Tom | last10 = Wisner | first10 = Katherine L. | chapter = Personality disorders and relational disorders: a research agenda for addressing crucial gaps in DSM | chapterurl = https://contextualscience.org/system/files/Kupfer,2002.pdf | editor-last1 = Kupfer | editor-first1 = David J. | editor-last2 = First | editor-first2 = Michael B. | editor-last3 = Regier | editor-first3 = Darrel A. | title = A research agenda for DSM-V | publisher = [[American Psychiatric Association]] | location = Washington, D.C. | year = 2002 | isbn = 9780890422922 | ref = harv }}</ref>{{rp|164, 166}} Couples with marital disorders sometimes come to clinical attention because the couple recognize long-standing dissatisfaction with their marriage and come to the [[clinician]] on their own initiative or are referred by an astute health care professional. Secondly, there is serious violence in the marriage that is -"usually the husband battering the wife".<ref name="Personality" />{{rp|163}} In these cases the emergency room or a legal authority often is the first to notify the [[clinician]]. Most importantly, marital violence "is a major risk factor for serious injury and even death and women in violent marriages are at much greater risk of being seriously injured or killed ([[National Advisory Council on Violence Against Women]] 2000)".<ref name="Personality" />{{rp|166}} The authors of this study add, "There is current considerable controversy over whether male-to-female marital violence is best regarded as a reflection of male [[psychopathology]] and control or whether there is an empirical base and clinical utility for conceptualizing these patterns as relational."<ref name="Personality" />{{rp|166}}

Recommendations for clinicians making a diagnosis of ''Marital Relational Disorder'' should include the assessment of actual or "potential" male violence as regularly as they assess the potential for suicide in depressed patients. Further, "clinicians should not relax their vigilance after a battered wife leaves her husband, because some data suggest that the period immediately following a marital separation is the period of greatest risk for the women. Many men will [[stalking|stalk]] and [[battery (crime)|batter]] their wives in an effort to get them to return or punish them for leaving. Initial assessments of the potential for violence in a marriage can be supplemented by standardized interviews and questionnaires, which have been reliable and valid aids in exploring marital violence more systematically."<ref name="Personality" />{{rp|166}}

The authors conclude with what they call "very recent information"<ref name="Personality" />{{rp|167, 168}} on the course of violent marriages, which suggests that "over time a husband's battering may abate somewhat, but perhaps because he has successfully [[intimidate]]d his wife. The risk of violence remains strong in a marriage in which it has been a feature in the past. Thus, treatment is essential here; the clinician cannot just wait and watch."<ref name="Personality" />{{rp|167, 168}} The most urgent clinical priority is the protection of the wife because she is the one most frequently at risk, and clinicians must be aware that supporting assertiveness by a battered wife may lead to more beatings or even death.<ref name="Personality" />{{rp|167, 168}}

====Honor killings====
[[Honor killings]] are a common form of violence against women in certain parts of the world. Honor killings are perpetrated by family members (usually husbands, fathers, uncles or brothers) against women in the family who are believed to have placed dishonor to the family. The death of the dishonorable woman is believed to restore honor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.stanford.edu/group/womenscourage/communitybasedsolutions/the_role_of_community_in_combating_honor_killings.html|title=the role of community in combating honor killings|website=web.stanford.edu|access-date=2018-12-08}}</ref> These killings are a traditional practice,{{where?|date=January 2019}} believed to have originated from tribal customs where an allegation against a woman can be enough to defile a family's reputation.<ref name="BBC_ethics">{{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = Ethics guide – Honour crimes | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/ethics/honourcrimes/crimesofhonour_1.shtml | work = [[BBC]] | access-date = 18 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last = Staff writer | title = Definition of honor killing | url = http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/honor%20killing | website = merriam-webster.com | publisher = [[Merriam-Webster]] | access-date = 18 November 2013}}</ref> Women are killed for reasons such as refusing to enter an [[arranged marriage]], being in a relationship that is disapproved by their relatives, attempting to leave a marriage, having sex outside marriage, becoming the victim of rape, dressing in ways that are deemed inappropriate.<ref name="BBC_ethics" /><ref name="bbc.co.uk">{{cite news | last = Harter | first = Pascale | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-13760895 | work= BBC News | title=Libya rape victims 'face honour killings' | date=14 June 2011| access-date = 18 November 2013}}</ref>

Honor killings are common in countries such as Afghanistan, Egypt, Iraq, Jordan, Lebanon, Libya, Morocco, Pakistan, Saudi Arabia, Syria, Turkey, Yemen.<ref name="bbc.co.uk"/><ref>{{cite web | last = UN Women | author-link = UN Women | title = Violence against women: work of the General Assembly on violence against women | url = https://www.un.org/womenwatch/daw/vaw/v-work-ga.htm | website = un.org/womenwatch | publisher = [[UN Women]], Violence Against Women | access-date = 18 November 2013}}
:''Listing for'':
:* {{cite book | last = UN Secretary-General | author-link = Secretary-General of the United Nations | title = Working towards the elimination of crimes against women committed in the name of honour | url = http://daccess-ods.un.org/access.nsf/Get?Open&DS=A/57/169&Lang=E | id = A/57/169 | publisher = [[United Nations General Assembly]] | language = English | date = 2 July 2002 }} [http://daccess-ods.un.org/access.nsf/Get?Open&DS=A/57/169&Lang=A Arabic pdf.] [http://daccess-ods.un.org/access.nsf/Get?Open&DS=A/57/169&Lang=C Chinese pdf.] [http://daccess-ods.un.org/access.nsf/Get?Open&DS=A/57/169&Lang=F French pdf.] [http://daccess-ods.un.org/access.nsf/Get?Open&DS=A/57/169&Lang=R Russian pdf.] [http://daccess-ods.un.org/access.nsf/Get?Open&DS=A/57/169&Lang=S Spanish pdf.]</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Ghanizada | title = 240 cases of honor killing recorded in Afghanistan, AIHRC | url = http://www.khaama.com/240-cases-of-honor-killing-recorded-in-afghanistan-aihrc-2177 | publisher = [[Khaama Press]] | location = Afghanistan | date = 9 June 2013 | access-date = 18 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = UPI |author-link=United Press International | title = AIHRC: 400 rape, honor killings registered in Afghanistan in 2 years | url = http://latinbusinesstoday.com/2013/06/aihrc-400-rape-honor-killings-registered-in-afghanistan-in-2-years/ | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150214224858/http://latinbusinesstoday.com/2013/06/aihrc-400-rape-honor-killings-registered-in-afghanistan-in-2-years/ | archive-date = 14 February 2015 | work = Latin Business Today | location = Kabul, Afghanistan | date = 10 June 2013 | access-date = 18 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last1 = Bayoumy | first1 = Yara | last2 = Kami | first2 = Aseel | title="Honor killings" require tougher laws, say Iraqi women | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/03/06/us-iraq-women-idUSTRE82510920120306 | work = Reuters | date=6 March 2012 | access-date = 18 November 2013}}</ref> Honor killings also occur in immigrant communities in Europe, the United States and Canada. Although honor killings are most often associated with the Middle East and South Asia, they occur in other parts of the world too.<ref name="BBC_ethics" /><ref>{{cite web | title = International Domestic Violence Issues | url = http://www.sanctuaryforfamilies.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=252&Itemid=259 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20141016194204/http://www.sanctuaryforfamilies.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=252&Itemid=259 | archive-date = 16 October 2014 | website = sanctuaryforfamilies.org | publisher = Sanctuary for Families }}</ref> In India, honor killings occur in the northern regions of the country, especially in the states of Punjab, Haryana, Bihar, Uttar Pradesh, Rajasthan, Jharkhand, Himachal Pradesh and Madhya Pradesh.<ref>{{cite news | last1 = Donald | first1 = Alice | last2 = Bishop | first2 = Hilary | title = World agenda: what justice? | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/specials/1817_wawryw/page4.shtml | publisher = [[BBC World Service]]  | access-date = 18 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = India court seeks 'honour killing' response | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10364986 | work = BBC News |date = 21 June 2010  | access-date = 18 November 2013}}</ref> In Turkey, honor killings are a serious problem in Southeastern Anatolia.<ref>{{cite news | last = Rainsford | first = Sarah | title = 'Honour' crime defiance in Turkey | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/4357158.stm | work = BBC News | date = 19 October 2005 | access-date = 18 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last = Kardam | first = Filiz | editor-last = Murray | editor-first = Genevra | title = The dynamics of honor killings in Turkey: prospects for action | url = http://www.unfpa.org/publications/dynamics-honour-killings-turkey | publisher = [[United Nations Development Programme]], Population Association (Turkey) and [[United Nations Population Fund]] | date = 2005 | access-date = 18 November 2013}} [http://www.unfpa.org/upload/lib_pub_file/676_filename_honourkillings.pdf Pdf.]</ref>

====Dowry violence====
[[File:Say no to dowry.jpg|thumb|upright|Anti-dowry poster in [[Bangalore, India]]]]

The custom of [[dowry]], which is common in South Asia, especially in India, is the trigger of many forms of violence against women. [[Bride burning]] is a form of violence against women in which a bride is killed at home by her husband or husband's family due to his dissatisfaction over the dowry provided by her family. [[Dowry death]] refers to the phenomenon of women and girls being killed or committing [[suicide]] due to disputes regarding dowry. Dowry violence is common in India, Pakistan, Bangladesh and Nepal. In India, in 2011 alone, the National Crime Records Bureau reported 8,618 dowry deaths, while unofficial figures suggest the numbers to be at least three times higher.<ref>{{cite book | last = UN Women | author-link = UN Women | title = Confronting dowry-related violence in India: women at the center of justice | url = http://www.unwomen.org/en/news/stories/2012/12/confronting-dowry-related-violence-in-india-women-at-the-center-of-justice | publisher = [[UN Women]] | date = 24 December 2012 | access-date = 18 November 2013 }}</ref>

====Forced marriage====
{{main|Forced marriage}}
[[File:Oskar Shmerling. Free love (Forced marriage). Molla Nasreddin.jpg|thumb|220px|left|Criticism of the [[Azerbaijani people|Azeri]] custom of [[forced marriage]], as depicted in the early 20th-century satirical periodical [[Molla Nasraddin (magazine)|Molla Nasraddin]]]]
A [[forced marriage]] is a marriage in which one or both of the parties is married against their will. Forced marriages are common in South Asia, the Middle East and Africa. The customs of [[bride price]] and [[dowry]], that exist in many parts of the world, contribute to this practice. A forced marriage is also often the result of a dispute between families, where the dispute is 'resolved' by giving a female from one family to the other.<ref>''Citations'':
* {{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = Ethics guide – Slavery: Modern slavery | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/ethics/slavery/modern/modern_1.shtml#section_2 | work = [[BBC]] | access-date = 5 September 2013}}
* {{cite book | last = Shahinian | first = Gulnara | title = Report of the Special Rapporteur on contemporary forms of slavery, including its causes and consequences, Gulnara Shahinian: Thematic report on servile marriage (A/HRC/21/41) | url = http://www.ohchr.org/Documents/HRBodies/HRCouncil/RegularSession/Session21/A-HRC-21-41_en.pdf | publisher =  United Nations. Human Rights Council Twenty-first session | date = 10 July 2012}}
* {{cite book | last = UNIFEM | author-link = United Nations Development Fund for Women | title = Ending violence against women & girls – Evidence, data and knowledge in the Pacific Island Countries: literature review and annotated bibliography |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708174234/http://www.undp.org.fj/pdf/unp/evaw.pdf | url = http://www.undp.org.fj/pdf/unp/evaw.pdf |url-status=dead |archivedate=8 July 2011 | publisher = [[United Nations Development Fund for Women|UNIFEM]] | date = August 2010 | accessdate = 8 July 2011}}</ref>

The custom of [[bride kidnapping]] continues to exist in some Central Asian countries such as Kyrgyzstan, Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan, and the Caucasus, or parts of Africa, especially Ethiopia. A girl or a woman is abducted by the would be groom, who is often helped by his friends. The victim is often raped by the would be groom, after which he may try to negotiate a bride price with the village elders to legitimize the marriage.<ref>''News articles'':
* {{cite news | last = Staff writer | title=World: Africa, Ethiopia: Revenge of the abducted bride | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/371944.stm | work =[[BBC News]] | date=18 June 1999 | access-date = 19 November 2013}}
* {{cite news| last = Gena | first = Alem | title = Ethiopia: Surviving forced marriage | url = http://www.irinnews.org/report/69993/ethiopia-surviving-forced-marriage | work = [[The New Humanitarian|IRIN]] | date = 23 February 2007 | accessdate = 3 April 2016}}
* {{cite book | last = PI | author-link = Pathfinder International | title = Report on causes and consequences of early marriage in Amhara Region |publisher=[[Pathfinder International]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130323124732/http://www.pathfinder.org/publications-tools/pdfs/Causes-and-Consequesnces-of-Early-Marriage-in-the-Amhara-Region-of-Ethiopia.pdf |archivedate=23 March 2013 |url-status=dead|url=http://www.pathfinder.org/publications-tools/pdfs/Causes-and-Consequesnces-of-Early-Marriage-in-the-Amhara-Region-of-Ethiopia.pdf | date = July 2006 |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref>

Forced and child marriages are practiced by some inhabitants in Tanzania. Girls are sold by their families to older men for financial benefits and often girls are married off as soon as they hit puberty, which can be as young as seven years old.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2014/10/29/tanzania-child-marriage-harms-girls|title=Tanzania: Child Marriage Harms Girls|date=2014-10-29|work=Human Rights Watch|access-date=2018-11-30|language=en}}</ref> To the older men, these young brides act as symbols of masculinity and accomplishment. Child brides endure forced sex, causing health risks and growth impediments.<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Ezer|first1=T|last2=et|first2=al.|date=2006|title=Child marriage and guardianship in tanzania: Robbing girls of their childhood and infantilizing women|url=https://heinonline.org/HOL/P?h=hein.journals/grggenl7&i=367&a=c3VueWJ1ZmZhbG8uZWR1|journal=Georgetown Journal of Gender and the Law|volume=Special Issue|pages=357–450|via=Hein}}</ref> Primary education is usually not completed for young girls in forced marriages. Married and pregnant students are often discriminated against, and expelled and excluded from school.<ref name=":0" /> The Law of Marriage Act currently does not address issues with guardianship and child marriage. The issue of child marriage is not addressed enough in this law, and only establishes a minimum age of 18 for the boys of Tanzania. A minimum age needs to be enforced for girls to stop these practices and provide them with equal rights and a less harmful life.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://heinonline.org/HOL/P?h=hein.journals/frdint38&i=660&a=c3VueWJ1ZmZhbG8uZWR1|title=- HeinOnline.org|website=heinonline.org|language=en|access-date=2018-11-30}}</ref>

====Force-feeding====
In some countries, notably Mauritania, young girls are forcibly fattened to prepare them for marriage, because obesity is seen as desirable. This practice of [[force-feeding]] is known as ''[[leblouh]]'' or ''gavage''.<ref>''Citations'':
* {{cite book | last = Popenoe | first = Rebecca | chapter = Getting fat | editor-last = Popenoe | editor-first = Rebecca | chapterurl = https://books.google.com/books?id=25H0_G9MG10C&pg=PA39 | title = Feeding desire: fatness, beauty, and sexuality among a Saharan people | pages = 33&ndash;50 | publisher = Routledge | location = London New York | year = 2004 | isbn = 9780415280969 | ref = harv }}
::''Book review'': {{cite web | last = Fan | title = Space and body modification: Rebecca Popenoe's ''Feeding Desire'' (blog) | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160304231342/http://www.savagemind.org/tag/body/ | archive-date = 4 March 2016 | url = http://www.savagemind.org/tag/body/ |publisher= Savage Mind via [[WordPress]] |date=3 August 2012 |accessdate=3 April 2016}}
* {{cite news | last = LaFraniere | first = Sharon | title = In Mauritania, seeking to end an overfed ideal | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2007/07/04/world/africa/04mauritania.html | work = [[The New York Times]] | quote = Girls as young as 5 and as old as 19 had to drink up to five gallons of fat-rich camel's or cow's milk daily, aiming for silvery stretch marks on their upper arms. If a girl refused or vomited, the village weight-gain specialist might squeeze her foot between sticks, pull her ear, pinch her inner thigh, bend her finger backward or force her to drink her own vomit. In extreme cases, girls die, due to a burst stomach. The practice was known as gavage, a French term for force-feeding geese to obtain foie gras. | date = 4 July 2007 | access-date = 30 June 2011}}</ref>

The practice goes back to the 11th century, and has been reported to have made a significant comeback after a [[2008 Mauritanian coup d'état|military junta took over the country in 2008]].<ref>{{cite news | last = Smith | first = Alex Duval | title = Girls being force-fed for marriage as junta revives fattening farms | url = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/mar/01/mauritania-force-feeding-marriage | work = [[The Observer]] | date = 1 March 2009 | access-date = 22 December 2015}}</ref>

====Abuse related to son-preference====
[[File:2011 Census sex ratio map for the states and Union Territories of India Boys to Girls 0 to 1 age group.svg|thumb|250px|left|A map of [[India]]'s child sex ratio, 2011.]]
[[File:2012 Birth Sex Ratio World Map.jpg|thumb|250px|World map of birth sex ratios, 2012]]
[[File:Chinese anti infanticide tract from 1800.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Chinese anti-infanticide tract circa 1800. China has a long history of son preference, which was aggravated after the enforcement of the [[one child policy]].]]
''Son preference'' is a custom rooted in gender inequality that is prevalent in many countries and found across religions and classes.<ref name="StopVAW_son">{{cite web | last = Staff writer | title = Son preference | url =http://www.stopvaw.org/harmful_practices_son_preference | website = stopvaw.org | publisher = Stop Violence Against Women | date = June 2010 | access-date = 3 October 2017}}</ref> Although preference for a specific sex of the child may be common in an abstract way in many cultures, when such preference is so strong as to lead to the rejection of the child or to violence against the mother, this crosses the line into [[domestic violence]], [[child abuse]] and violence against women. Such forms of son preference are common especially in parts of [[South Asia]], [[East Asia]] and the [[Caucasus]]. Manifestations of such practices include [[sex selective abortion]], [[female infanticide]], [[child abandonment|female child abandonment]], as well as favoring sons with regard to allocating of family resources.<ref name="StopVAW_son" />

[[China]] and [[India]] have a very strong son preference. In China, the [[one child policy]] was largely responsible for an unbalanced sex ratio. Sex-selective abortion, as well as rejection of girl children is common. [[The Dying Rooms]] is a 1995 [[television]] [[documentary film]] about Chinese state orphanages, which documented how parents abandoned their newborn girls into [[orphanages]], where the staff would leave the children in rooms to die of thirst, or starvation.
Another manifestation of son preference is the violence inflicted against mothers who give birth to girls.<ref>''News articles'':
* {{cite news | last = Sarwary | first = Bilal | title = Afghan woman is killed 'for giving birth to a girl' | url = https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-16787534 | work = [[BBC News]] | location = Kabul, Afghanistan | date = 30 January 2012 | access-date = 3 October 2017}}
* {{cite news | last = Agarwal | first = Keshav | title = 23-year-old woman killed for giving birth to twin daughters | url = http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bareilly/23-year-old-woman-killed-for-giving-birth-to-twin-daughters/articleshow/57785767.cms | work = [[The Times of India]] | date = 23 March 2017 | access-date = 3 October 2017}}
* {{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = 56 killed for giving birth to girl child in Pakistan | url = http://www.deccanchronicle.com/131127/news-world/article/56-killed-giving-birth-girl-child-pakistan | work = [[Deccan Chronicle]] | location = Hyderabad, Telangana, India | date = 27 November 2013 | access-date = 3 October 2017}}</ref>

===Acid throwing===
{{main|Acid throwing}}
[[File:Acid attack victim.jpg|left|Acid attack victim in [[Cambodia]]|thumb|250px]]
[[Acid throwing]], also called acid attack, or vitriolage, is defined as the act of throwing acid onto the body of a person "with the intention of injuring or disfiguring [them] out of jealousy or revenge".<ref>{{Cite book | last =Vig |first= Krishan| chapter = Corrosive poisons: vitriolage | chapterurl = https://books.google.com/books?id=Ip1rAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA462 | editor-last =Vig |editor-first=Krishan | title=Textbook of forensic medicine and toxicology: principles and practice | page=462 |publisher=Elsevier | location = India | year=2014 |edition=5th | isbn=9788131226841 }}</ref> The most common types of acid used in these attacks are sulfuric, nitric, or hydrochloric acid.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Welsh | first = Jane | title = "It was like burning in hell": A comprehensive exploration of acid attack violence | journal = Carolina Papers on International Health | volume = 32 |publisher=Center for Global Initiatives, [[University of North Carolina]] |accessdate=3 April 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130123191359/http://cgi.unc.edu/uploads/media_items/it-was-like-burning-in-hell-a-comparative-exploration-of-acid-attack-violence.original.pdf|url=http://cgi.unc.edu/uploads/media_items/it-was-like-burning-in-hell-a-comparative-exploration-of-acid-attack-violence.original.pdf |archivedate=23 January 2013| date = Fall 2006}}</ref> Perpetrators of these attacks throw [[acid]] at their victims, usually at their faces, burning them, and damaging [[skin]] tissue, often exposing and sometimes dissolving the bones.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Swanson | first = Jordan | title = Acid attacks: Bangladesh's efforts to stop the violence | journal = Harvard Health Policy Review | volume = 3 | issue = 1 | page = 3 | publisher = Harvard Internfaculty Initiative in Health Policy | date = Spring 2002 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20060117184047/http://hcs.harvard.edu/~epihc/currentissue/spring2002/swanson-3.php | archive-date = 17 January 2006 | url = http://hcs.harvard.edu:80/~epihc/currentissue/spring2002/swanson-3.php | ref = harv | url-status = dead}}</ref> The long term consequences of these attacks include [[blindness]] and permanent [[scarring]] of the face and body.<ref>{{cite news | last = AP | author-link = Associated Press |url=http://archives.cnn.com/2000/ASIANOW/south/11/11/bangladesh.acid.ap/index.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070922210725/http://archives.cnn.com/2000/ASIANOW/south/11/11/bangladesh.acid.ap/index.html |archivedate=22 September 2007 |title= Bangladesh combats an acid onslaught against women |work=[[CNN]]|date= 12 November 2000 |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book | last1 = Bahl | first1 = Taur | last2 = Syed | first2 = M. H. | title = Encyclopaedia of Muslim world | publisher = Anmol Publications | location = New Delhi | year = 2003 | isbn = 9788126114191}}</ref> Women and girls are the victims in 75-80% of cases.<ref>{{cite news | last = de Castella | first = Tom | title=How many acid attacks are there? | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-23631395 | work=[[BBC News]] | date=9 August 2013 |accessdate= 18 November 2013}}</ref> Acid attacks are often connected to domestic disputes, including dowry disputes, and refusal of a proposal of marriage, or of sexual advances. Such attacks are common in South Asia, in countries such as Bangladesh, Pakistan, India; and in Southeast Asia, especially in Cambodia.<ref>''Articles'':
* {{cite news | last = Shackle | first = Samira | title = Acid attacks in Pakistan: A sorry litany of male egotism | url = http://www.newstatesman.com/world-affairs/2012/11/acid-attacks-pakistan-sorry-litany-male-egotism | work = [[New Statesman]] | date = 9 November 2012 |accessdate= 8 September 2013}} ''Interview with [[Sharmeen Obaid-Chinoy]] one of the directors the documentary "[[Saving Face (2012 film)|Saving Face]]".''
* {{cite news | last = CBC | title = Longueuil woman burned and in coma after acid attack|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2012/08/28/nikolas-stefanatos-quebec-acid-attack_n_1838232.html |work=[[HuffPost]] | date = 28 October 2012 |accessdate=8 September 2013}}
* {{cite news |last = Ungaro | first = Cosima | title = Nurbanu, Bangladeshi woman, forced to return to husband after acid attack | url = https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/11/28/nurbanu-acid-attack_n_2206621.html |work=[[HuffPost]] |accessdate= 8 September 2013  |date=28 November 2012}}
* {{cite news | last =Scholte| first =Marianne| title =Acid attacks in Bangladesh: a voice for the victims| work = [[Spiegel Online]]| url =http://www.spiegel.de/international/0,1518,406485,00.html | date = 17 March 2006 | accessdate = 21 March 2008}}
* {{cite book | last = Various |title=Combating acid violence in Bangladesh, India, and Cambodia |url= http://www.lawschool.cornell.edu/womenandjustice/upload/Combating-Acid-Violence-Report.pdf |publisher= [[Cornell Law School#Institutes and Programs|Avon Global Center for Women and Justice at Cornell Law School]], [[New York City Bar Association|Committee on International Human Rights of the, New York City Bar Association]], [[Cornell Law School#Campus|Cornell Law School International Human Rights Clinic]] and the Virtue Foundation | location = New York |accessdate=3 April 2016}}
* {{cite book | last = CASC | title = Breaking the silence: addressing acid attacks in Cambodia | url = http://www.cambodianacidsurvivorscharity.org/docs/breaking_the_silence.pdf |publisher=Cambodian Acid Survivors Charity (CASC) |accessdate=3 April 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131219010314/http://www.cambodianacidsurvivorscharity.org/docs/breaking_the_silence.pdf |archivedate=19 December 2013| date = May 2010}}</ref>

===Reproductive coercion===
[[File:Mauricio rugendas - el malon.jpg|thumb|The painting depicts a Chilean woman being kidnapped during a [[malón]]. [[Bride kidnapping]] for the purpose of [[forced marriage]] and [[forced pregnancy]] was common through the history in many countries.]]
{{Main|Reproductive coercion|Forced pregnancy|Bride kidnapping}}
Reproductive coercion is a form of [[domestic violence|domestic]] or [[intimate partner violence]], that involves violent, manipulative or deceptive behavior against [[reproductive health]] or [[reproductive rights]] within an intimate relation and includes a collection of behaviors intended to lead to [[forced pregnancy]].<ref name="ACOG">{{cite journal | last = Committee on Health Care for Underserved Women | title = Committee Opinion No. 554: Reproductive and Sexual Coercion | journal = [[Obstetrics & Gynecology (journal)|Obstetrics and Gynecology]] | volume = 121 | issue = 2 Pt 1 | pages = 411&ndash;415 | publisher = [[Lippincott Williams & Wilkins|LWW]] | pmid = 23344307 | doi = 10.1097/01.AOG.0000426427.79586.3b | date = February 2013 | url = https://www.acog.org/Resources-And-Publications/Committee-Opinions/Committee-on-Health-Care-for-Underserved-Women/Reproductive-and-Sexual-Coercion | ref = harv }}</ref> Reproductive coercion is used to maintain power, control, and domination within a relationship and over a partner through an unwanted pregnancy. It is considered a serious public health issue.<ref name="ACOG"/><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Chamberlain | first1 = Linda | last2 = Levenson | first2 = Rebecca | title = Reproductive health and partner violence guidelines: an integrated response to intimate partner Violence and reproductive coercion | url = http://www.futureswithoutviolence.org/userfiles/file/HealthCare/Repro_Guide.pdf | publisher = Family Violence Prevention Fund | location = San Francisco | date = 2010 }}</ref> This reproductive control is highly correlated to [[unintended pregnancy]].<ref>{{cite journal | last = Coker | first = Ann L. | title = Does physical intimate partner violence affect sexual health? A systematic review | journal = [[Trauma, Violence, & Abuse]] | volume = 8 | issue = 2| pages = 149&ndash;177 | publisher = [[SAGE Publications|Sage]] | pmid = 17545572 | doi = 10.1177/1524838007301162 | date = April 2007 | s2cid = 34515385 | ref = harv }}</ref>

Forced pregnancy is the practice of forcing a woman or girl to become [[pregnant]], often as part of a [[forced marriage]], including by means of [[bride kidnapping]], through rape (including [[marital rape]], [[war rape]] and [[genocidal rape]]) or as part of a program of breeding [[slave]]s (see [[Slave breeding in the United States]]). In the 20th century, state mandated forced marriage with the aim of increasing the population was practiced by some authoritarian governments, notably during the [[Khmer Rouge]] regime in [[Cambodia]], which systematically forced people into marriages ordering them to have children, in order to increase the population and continue the revolution.<ref>{{cite book | last = Anderson | first = Natalae | title = Memorandum: Charging forced marriage as a crime against humanity | url = http://www.d.dccam.org/Abouts/Intern/Natalae_Forced_marriage.pdf | publisher = Documentation Center of Cambodia | date = 22 September 2010 | access-date = 8 October 2017 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171020153617/http://www.d.dccam.org/Abouts/Intern/Natalae_Forced_marriage.pdf | archive-date = 20 October 2017 | url-status = dead }}</ref> Forced pregnancy is strongly connected to the custom of [[bride price]].<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Bawah | first1 = Ayaga Agula | last2 = Akweongo | first2 = Patricia | last3 = Simmons | first3 = Ruth | last4 = Phillips | first4 = James F. | title = Women's fears and men's anxieties: the impact of family planning on gender relations in Northern Ghana | journal = [[Studies in Family Planning]] | volume = 30 | issue = 1 | pages = 54&ndash;66 | publisher = [[Wiley-Blackwell|Wiley]] on behalf of the [[Population Council]] | date = 1999 | url = https://www.popcouncil.org/research/womens-fears-and-mens-anxieties-the-impact-of-family-planning-on-gender-rel | ref = harv | doi=10.1111/j.1728-4465.1999.00054.x| pmid = 10216896 | hdl = 2027.42/73927 }} [http://www.popcouncil.org/uploads/pdfs/councilarticles/sfp/SFP301Bawah.pdf Pdf.]</ref>

Within the discourse on reproductive rights, the issue of [[abortion]] is often debated. [[Abortion law]] falls within the jurisdiction of each country, although [[forced abortion]] is prohibited by international law. The [[Convention on preventing and combating violence against women and domestic violence|Istanbul Convention]] prohibits forced abortion and [[forced sterilization]] (Article 39).<ref>{{cite book | last = CoE | author-link = Council of Europe | title = Convention on preventing and combating violence against women and domestic violence | url = https://rm.coe.int/168046031c | publisher = [[Council of Europe]] | date = 12 April 2011 }}</ref> The issue of ''forced continuation of pregnancy'' (i.e. denying a woman safe and legal abortion) is also seen by some organizations as a violation of women's rights, although there are no binding international obligations on this issue. However, the [[Committee on the Elimination of Discrimination against Women]] considers the criminalization of abortion a "violations of women's sexual and reproductive health and rights" and a form of "gender based violence"; paragraph 18 of its ''General recommendation No. 35 on gender based violence against women, updating general recommendation No. 19'' states, "Violations of women’s sexual and reproductive health and rights, such as forced sterilizations, forced abortion, forced pregnancy, ''criminalisation of abortion'', ''denial or delay of safe abortion and post abortion care'', ''forced continuation of pregnancy'', abuse and mistreatment of women and girls seeking sexual and reproductive health information, goods and services, are forms of gender based violence that, depending on the circumstances, may amount to torture or cruel, [[inhuman or degrading treatment]]."<ref>{{cite book | last = Committee on the Elimination of Discrimination Against Women | author-link = Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination Against Women#Committee on the Elimination of Discrimination Against Women | title = General recommendation No. 35 on gender-based violence against women, updating general recommendation No. 19 | url = http://tbinternet.ohchr.org/Treaties/CEDAW/Shared%20Documents/1_Global/CEDAW_C_GC_35_8267_E.pdf | publisher = [[Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination Against Women]] (CEDAW) | id = CEDAW/C/GC/35 | date = 14 July 2017}}</ref>

===Mob violence===
There have been [[Hassi Messaoud mob attacks against women|mob attacks against single women]] in [[Hassi Messaoud]], [[Algeria]] in 2001.<ref name="Amnesty">{{cite web|title=Algerian authorities must investigate and stop attacks against women |url=https://www.amnesty.org.au/news/comments/22931/ |publisher=Amnesty International|accessdate=13 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110903140432/http://www.amnesty.org.au/news/comments/22931/|archivedate=3 September 2011}}</ref> 95 women had been attacked by mobs of men, with at least six fatalities, although the authorities denied this.<ref name=":2">{{Cite journal|last=Grozelle|first=Renee S.|date=2015|title=Mob Violence Against Women in Algeria: A Historical Case Analysis|url=http://www.inquiriesjournal.com/articles/1016/mob-violence-against-women-in-algeria-a-historical-case-analysis|journal=Inquiries Journal|language=en|volume=7|issue=3}}</ref> As of 2011, similar mob attacks against women were continuing in [[Hassi Messaoud]] and elsewhere in Algeria, notably [[M'Sila, Algeria|M'sila]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Stop renewed attacks on women |url=http://www.wluml.org/node/7420|publisher=Women Living Under Muslim Laws|accessdate=13 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Algerian authorities must investigate and stop attacks against women|url=https://www.amnesty.org.au/news/comments/22931/|publisher=Amnesty International|accessdate=13 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110903140432/http://www.amnesty.org.au/news/comments/22931/|archivedate=3 September 2011}}</ref> However, mob violence against women in the country dates back decades, and increased specifically after gaining independence from France in 1962, which was followed by return to stricter religious norms.<ref name=":2" />

According to [[Amnesty International]], "some women have been sexually abused" and were targeted "not just because they are women, but because they are living alone and are economically independent".<ref name="Amnesty" />

=== Dating abuse ===
{{See|Dating abuse|Teen dating violence}}
Dating abuse or dating violence is the perpetration of coercion, intimidation or assault in the context of [[dating]] or [[courtship]]. It is also when one partner tries to maintain [[abusive power and control]]. Dating violence is defined by the CDC as "the physical, sexual, psychological, or emotional violence within a dating relationship, including stalking".<ref>{{cite web | title = Intimate partner violence: teen dating violence | url = https://www.cdc.gov/violenceprevention/intimatepartnerviolence/teen_dating_violence.html | website = cdc.gov | publisher = [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] | date = 2016 | accessdate = 21 October 2017 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181230230859/https://www.cdc.gov/ViolencePrevention/intimatepartnerviolence/teen_dating_violence.html | archive-date = 30 December 2018 | url-status = dead }} [https://www.cdc.gov/violenceprevention/pdf/teen-dating-violence-factsheet-a.pdf Fact sheet pdf.]</ref> In some countries it is common for older men to engage in "compensated dating" with underage girls. Such relationships are called [[enjo kōsai]] in Japan, and are also common in Asian countries such as Taiwan, South Korea, Hong Kong. The WHO condemned "economically coerced sex (e.g. school girls having sex with "sugar daddies" ([[Sugar baby]] in return for school fees)" as a form of violence against women.<ref name="WHO_VAW" />

===Sexual violence on college campuses===
{{See|Campus sexual assault}}
Sexual violence on college campuses is considered a major problem in the United States. According to the conclusion of a major Campus Sexual Assault (CSA) Study: "The CSA Study data suggest women at universities are at considerable risk for experiencing sexual assault."<ref>{{cite book  | last1 = Krebs | first1 = Christopher P. | last2 =Lindquist | first2 = Christine H. | last3 =Warner | first3 = Tara D. | last4 =Fisher | first4 = Bonnie S. | last5 =Martin | first5 = Sandra L. | title = Campus sexual assault (CSA) study: final report | publisher = [[RTI International]] | url = https://www.ncjrs.gov/App/Publications/abstract.aspx?ID=243011 | date = October 2007 }} {{NCJ|243011}} [https://www.ncjrs.gov/pdffiles1/nij/grants/221153.pdf Pdf.]</ref> Sexual violence on campus has been researched in other countries too, such as Canada,<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = DeKeseredy | first1 = Walter | last2 = Kelly|  first2 = Katharine | title = The incidence and prevalence of woman abuse in Canadian university and college dating relationships | journal = [[Canadian Journal of Sociology]] | volume = 18 | issue = 2 | pages = 137&ndash;159 | publisher = [[University of Alberta]] | jstor = 3341255 | doi = 10.2307/3341255 | date = 1993 | ref = harv }}</ref> the UK,<ref>{{cite book | last = NUS | author-link = National Union of Students (United Kingdom) |title=Hidden Marks: A study of women student's experiences of harassment, stalking, violence, and sexual assault | url = http://www.nus.org.uk/Global/NUS_hidden_marks_report_2nd_edition_web.pdf | publisher = [[National Union of Students (United Kingdom)|National Union of Students]] | location = London, UK | date = 2011| edition = 2nd|accessdate=10 January 2015}}</ref> and New Zealand.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Gavey | authorlink=Nicola Gavey|first = Nicola | title = Sexual victimization prevalence among New Zealand university students | journal = [[Journal of Consulting and Clinical Psychology]] | volume = 59 | issue = 3 | pages = 464&ndash;466 | publisher = [[American Psychological Association]] via [[PsycINFO|PsycNET]] | doi = 10.1037/0022-006X.59.3.464 | date = June 1991 | pmid=2071732| ref = harv }}</ref>

===Restrictions on freedom of movement===
Women are, in many parts of the world, severely restricted in their [[freedom of movement]].
Freedom of movement is an essential right, recognized by international instruments, including Article 15 (4) of [[CEDAW]].<ref>{{cite book | last =  UN General Assembly | author-link =  UN General Assembly | title = The convention on the elimination of all forms of discrimination against women (CEDAW) | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140326154350/http://www.un.org/womenwatch/daw/cedaw/text/econvention.htm | archive-date = 26 March 2014 | url = http://www.un.org/womenwatch/daw/cedaw/text/econvention.htm | publisher = [[UN Women|UN Women, Division for the Advancement of Women]] | date = 1979 | access-date = 3 October 2017}}</ref> Nevertheless, in some countries, women are not legally allowed to leave home without a [[Wali (Islamic legal guardian)|male guardian]] (male relative or husband).<ref>{{cite news | last = Lee | first = Dave | title = Saudi Arabian woman challenges male guardianship laws | url = https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-13932287 | work = [[BBC World Service]] | date = 29 June 2011 | access-date = 3 October 2017}}</ref> Even in countries where there are no laws against women traveling alone, there are strong social norms, such as [[purdah]] - a religious and social practice of female [[seclusion]] prevalent especially among some [[Muslim]] and [[Hindu]] communities in [[South Asia]]. Many countries have laws on what type of clothing women may or may not wear in public (see [[Hijab by country]]). Women in some cultures are forced into [[social isolation]] during their [[menstruation|menstrual period]]s. In parts of Nepal for instance, they are forced to live in sheds, are forbidden to touch men or even to enter the courtyard of their own homes, and are barred from consuming milk, yogurt, butter, meat, and various other foods, for fear they will contaminate those goods. (see [[Chhaupadi]]). Women have died during this period because of starvation, bad weather, or bites by snakes.<ref>''Articles'':
* {{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = PM concerned over death of woman in Chaupadi | url = http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2016-11-19/pm-concerned-over-death-of-woman-in-chaupadi.html | work = [[The Kathmandu Post]] | date = 19 November 2016 | access-date = 3 October 2017}}
* {{cite news| last = Pokharel | first = Sugam | title = Nepali 'mensuration hut' ritual claims life of teenage girl | url = http://edition.cnn.com/2017/07/10/asia/nepal-menstruation-hut-deaths-outrage/index.html | work = [[CNN]] | date = 10 July 2017 | access-date = 3 October 2017}}
* {{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = Nepal criminalises banishing menstruating women to huts | url = https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-40885748 | work = [[BBC News]] | date = 10 August 2017 | access-date = 3 October 2017}}
* {{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = Nepali girl dies due to banned mensuration practice | url = http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/12/nepali-girl-dies-menstruation-chhaupadi-161219090727200.html | work = [[Al Jazeera]] | date = December 2016 | access-date = 3 October 2017}}</ref> In cultures where women are restricted from being in public places, by law or custom, women who break such restrictions often face violence.<ref>{{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = Freedom of movement and women's economic empowerment | url = https://www.empowerwomen.org/en/who-we-are/news/2016/2/freedom-of-movement-and-womens-economic-empowerment | work = Empower Women | date = February 2016 | access-date = 3 October 2017}}</ref>

===Denial of medical care===
[[File:Maternal mortality rate worldwide.jpg|thumb|300px|[[Maternal Mortality Rate]] worldwide, as defined by the number of maternal deaths per 100,000 live births from any cause related to or aggravated by pregnancy or its management, excluding accidental or incidental causes.<ref name=CIA2010>[https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/rankorder/2223rank.html?countryName=Australia&countryCode=as&regionCode=aus&rank=156#as Country Comparison: Maternal Mortality Rate] in [[:en:The World Factbook|The CIA World Factbook]]. Date of Information: 2010</ref>]]
Women in many parts of the world are often denied medical care. Denial of access to 
health assistance, along with denial of access to other services, is a form of socioeconomic violence against women.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.womensrefugeecommission.org/images/zdocs/gl_sgbv03_01.pdf|title=chapter1: Overview of sexual and gender-based violence|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> According to the WHO, "Discrimination in health care settings takes many forms and is often manifested when an individual or group is denied access to health care services that are otherwise available to others. It can also occur through denial of services that are only needed by certain groups, such as women."<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/27-06-2017-joint-united-nations-statement-on-ending-discrimination-in-health-care-settings|title=Joint United Nations statement on ending discrimination in health care settings|website=www.who.int}}</ref>

Women may be denied medical care for numerous reasons, including lack of necessary [[freedom of movement]] allowing women to leave home so they can go to a medical facility, lack of financial resources, the need (in law or in practice) for a male relative or husband to consent to the medical care of the woman. A common consequence of denial of women's medical care is [[maternal mortality]]. Globally, there are more than 300.000 cases of maternal mortality yearly, with 99% of all maternal deaths occurring in developing countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/fs348/en/|title=Maternal mortality|website=World Health Organization}}</ref>

Denial of medical care often occurs with regard to reproductive and sexual health. Sometimes women themselves avoid the medical system for fear of being reported to the police or facing family violence due to having [[premarital sex]] or being the victims of [[sexual violence]]. In some parts of Latin America, with very strict anti-abortion laws, pregnant women avoid the medical system due to fear of being investigated by the authorities if they have a miscarriage, or a stillbirth, or other problems with the pregnancy. Prosecuting such women is quite common in places such as [[El Salvador]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2017/07/el-salvador-rape-survivor-sentenced-to-30-years-in-jail-under-extreme-anti-abortion-law/|title=El Salvador: Rape survivor sentenced to 30 years in jail under extreme anti-abortion law|website=www.amnesty.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/world-latin-america-32491838/el-salvador-women-jailed-for-miscarriages|title=Jailed for a miscarriage|website=BBC News}}</ref><ref name="ReferenceB">Prügl, E. (Lecturer) (2 December 2013). Gender and International Affairs 2013. INTERNATIONAL FEMINIST MOVEMENTS. Lecture conducted from The Graduate Institute of International and Development Studies (IHEID), Geneva, Switzerland.</ref><ref name="reuters.com">{{cite news|last=Hosenball |first=Mark |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/06/06/us-usa-wiretaps-verizon-idUSBRE95502920130606 |title=Obama administration defends massive phone record collection |work=Reuters |date=6 June 2013 |accessdate=6 March 2016}}</ref>

In developed societies, women face medial discrimination in that female health concerns are often dismissed or downplayed, especially when reproductive health is concerned. Research since 2001 has consistently shown that medical practitioners have been "dismissing, misdiagnosing, or cluelessly shrugging" at women seeking medical assistance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2018/08/womens-health-care-gaslighting/567149/|title=The Doctor Doesn't Listen to Her. But the Media Is Starting To.|last=Fetters|first=Ashley|date=2018-08-10|website=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Pagán|first=Camille Noe|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/03/well/live/when-doctors-downplay-womens-health-concerns.html|title=When Doctors Downplay Women's Health Concerns|date=2018-05-03|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>

Denial of medical care for women has led to the exclusion of female needs in medical research and diagnosis, leading to a male bias in medical trials at the expense of women's health.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Jackson|first=Gabrielle|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2019/nov/13/the-female-problem-male-bias-in-medical-trials|title=The female problem: how male bias in medical trials ruined women's health|date=2019-11-13|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-24|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>

===Stalking===
{{Main|Stalking}}
Stalking is unwanted or obsessive attention by an individual or group toward another person, often manifested through persistent [[harassment]], [[intimidation]], or following/monitoring of the victim. Stalking is often understood as "course of conduct directed at a specific person that would cause a reasonable person to feel fear".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.victimsofcrime.org/our-programs/stalking-resource-center/stalking-information |title=Stalking information |website =victimsofcrime.org | publisher = Stalking Resource Center |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref> Although stalkers are frequently portrayed as being strangers, they are most often known people, such as former or current partners, friends, colleagues or acquaintances. In the U.S., a survey by NVAW found that only 23% of female victims were stalked by strangers.<ref name="victimsofcrime.org">{{cite journal | last1 = McFarlane | first1 = Judith M. | last2 = Campbell | first2 = Jacquelyn C. | last3 = Wilt | first3 = Susan | last4 = Sachs | first4 = Carolyn J. | last5 = Ulrich | first5 = Yvonne | last6 = Xu | first6 = Xiao | title = Stalking and intimate partner femicide | journal = [[Homicide Studies]] | volume = 3 | issue = 4 | pages = 300&ndash;316 | publisher = [[Sage Publications|Sage]] | doi = 10.1177/1088767999003004003 | date = November 1999 | s2cid = 145522253 | ref = harv }} [http://victimsofcrime.org/docs/src/mcfarlane-j-m-campbell-j-c-wilt-s-sachs-c-j-ulrich-y-xu-x-1999.pdf Pdf.]</ref> Stalking by partners can be very dangerous, as sometimes it can escalate into severe violence, including murder.<ref name="victimsofcrime.org"/> Police statistics from the 1990s in Australia indicated that 87.7% of stalking offenders were male and 82.4% of stalking victims were female.<ref>{{cite book |last=Dussuyer |first=Inez |url=http://www.aic.gov.au/media_library/conferences/stalking/dussuyer.pdf |title=Is stalking legislation effective in protecting victims? |publisher=[[Australian Institute of Criminology]] |location=Sydney |date=December 2000 |accessdate=3 April 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304052637/http://www.aic.gov.au/media_library/conferences/stalking/dussuyer.pdf |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead}} Paper presented at the ''Stalking: Criminal Justice Responses Conference'' convened by the [[Australian Institute of Criminology]] and held in Sydney 7–8 December 2000.</ref>

===Sexual harassment===
{{Main|Sexual harassment}}
Sexual harassment is abusive, uninvited and unwelcome behavior of a sexual nature, typically in the work/studying place, which may include [[intimidation]], [[bullying]] or [[coercion]] of a sexual nature, or the inappropriate promise of rewards in exchange for sexual favors. It can be verbal or physical, and it is often perpetrated by a person in a position of authority against a subordinate.<ref>{{cite web | last = UN Women | author-link = UN Women|url=https://www.un.org/womenwatch/osagi/pdf/whatissh.pdf |title=What is sexual harassment |publisher=[[UN Women]] |accessdate=3 April 2016}}
:''Citing'':
:* {{cite book | last = BNA | author-link = Bureau of national affairs  | title = Preventing workplace harassment: a factsheet for employees | publisher = [[Bureau of national affairs|BNA Communications, Inc.]] | location = Washington, DC | issn = 1544-7820 | year = 1992 }} [https://www.bna.com/uploadedFiles/BNA_V2/Legal/Products/Books/Legal_Reference/shfsSample.pdf Sample of 2016 edition.]</ref> In the United States, sexual harassment is a form of discrimination that violates Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964. The [[Council of Europe Convention on preventing and combating violence against women and domestic violence]] defines sexual harassment as: "any form of unwanted verbal, non-verbal or physical conduct of a sexual nature with the purpose or effect of violating the dignity of a person, in particular when creating an intimidating, hostile, degrading, humiliating or offensive environment".<ref name="COE 210" />

===Human trafficking and forced prostitution===
[[File:Map3.3Trafficking compressed.jpg|thumb|230px|right|A world map showing countries by prevalence of female trafficking]]
{{Main|Human trafficking|Forced prostitution}}
Human trafficking refers to the acquisition of persons by improper means such as force, fraud or deception, with the aim of [[Exploitation of labour|exploiting]] them.<ref>{{cite web| last = UNODC| author-link =United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime|url=http://www.unodc.org/unodc/human-trafficking/index.html?ref=menuside |title=UNODC on human trafficking and migrant smuggling (index) |publisher=[[United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime]] |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref> The [[Protocol to Prevent, Suppress and Punish Trafficking in Persons, especially Women and Children]] states,<ref>{{cite web | last = OSCE | author-link = OSCE|url=http://www.osce.org/odihr/19223 |title=U.N. protocol to prevent, suppress and punish trafficking in persons, especially women and children, supplementing the United Nations convention against transnational organized crime |publisher=[[Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe]] |date=15 November 2000 |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref>

: "Trafficking in persons" shall mean the recruitment, transportation, transfer, harbouring or receipt of persons, by means of the threat or use of force or other forms of coercion, of abduction, of fraud, of deception, of the abuse of power or of a position of vulnerability or of the giving or receiving of payments or benefits to achieve the consent of a person having control over another person, for the purpose of exploitation. Exploitation shall include, at a minimum, the exploitation of the prostitution of others or other forms of sexual exploitation, forced labour or services, slavery or practices similar to slavery, servitude or the removal of organs.

Because of the illegal nature of trafficking, reliable data on its extent is very limited.<ref name="apps.who.int">{{cite book | last = WHO | author-link = World Health Organization|title=Understanding and addressing violence against women: Human trafficking |url=http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/77394/1/WHO_RHR_12.42_eng.pdf | id = WHO/RHR/12.42 |publisher=[[World Health Organization]] | date = 2012 |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref> The [[World Health Organization|WHO]] states "Current evidence strongly suggests that those who are trafficked into the [[sex industry]] and as domestic servants are more likely to be women and children."<ref name="apps.who.int"/>
A 2006 study in Europe on trafficked women found that the women were subjected to serious forms of abuse, such as physical or sexual violence, that affected their physical and mental health.<ref name="apps.who.int"/>

[[Forced prostitution]] is [[prostitution]] that takes place as a result of [[coercion]] by a third party. In forced prostitution, the party/parties who force the victim to be subjected to unwanted sexual acts exercise control over the victim.<ref>{{cite web | last = McDougall | first = Gay J. | author-link = Gay McDougall|url=http://www.unhchr.ch/huridocda/huridoca.nsf/0/3d25270b5fa3ea998025665f0032f220?OpenDocument#Bsl |title=Report of the Special Rapporteur on systematic rape, sexual slavery and slavery-like practices during armed conflict | id = E/CN.4/Sub.2/1998/13 | publisher = [[United Nations Economic and Social Council]] (ECOSOC) |accessdate=25 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130112211407/http://www.unhchr.ch/huridocda/huridoca.nsf/0/3d25270b5fa3ea998025665f0032f220?OpenDocument |archivedate=12 January 2013 }}</ref>

===Mistreatment of widows===
[[File:Balinese rite of Suttee in Houtman 1597 Verhael vande Reyse ... Naer Oost Indien.jpg|thumb|200px|Description of the [[Bali]]nese rite of ''Suttee'', in Houtman's 1597 ''Verhael vande Reyse ... Naer Oost Indien'']]
{{Main|Widow}}
{{See also|Widow inheritance|Sexual cleansing#Widow cleansing|l2=Sexual cleansing}}
A widow is a woman whose spouse has died. In some parts of the world, widows are subjected to serious forms of abuse, often fueled by traditional practices such as [[widow inheritance]].<ref>{{cite book | last = Owen | first = Margaret | chapter = Human rights, equality and legal protection | chapterurl = https://books.google.com/books?id=Bh8sGfNKUTEC&pg=PA181 | editor-last = Owen | editor-first = Margaret | title = A world of widows | publisher = Zed Books | location = London Atlantic Highlands, New Jersey | year = 1996 | isbn = 9781856494205 | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/worldofwidows0000owen }}</ref> The sacrifice of widows (such as [[Sati (practice)|sati]]) has been prevalent historically in various cultures (especially in [[India]]). Although sati in India is today an almost defunct practice, isolated incidents have occurred in recent years, such as the 1987 sati of [[Roop Kanwar]], as well as several incidents in rural areas in 2002,<ref>{{cite news | last = Staff writer | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/2178102.stm | work=[[BBC News]] | title=Arrests in Indian ritual burning | date=7 August 2002 | access-date = 25 January 2014}}</ref> and 2006.<ref>{{cite news | last = Staff writer | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/5366506.stm | work=[[BBC News]] | title=Sons arrested in sati death probe | date=21 September 2006 | access-date = 25 January 2014}}</ref> Those likely to be accused and killed as [[Modern witch-hunts|witche]]s are often widows.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/asia/21725040-law-criminalising-sorcery-was-only-repealed-2013-gruesome-fate-witches-papua-new|title=The gruesome fate of "witches" in Papua New Guinea|newspaper=The Economist|date=13 July 2017 |accessdate=23 July 2017}}</ref> In parts of Africa, such as in Kenya, widows are viewed as impure and need to be 'cleansed'. This often requires having sex with someone. Those refusing to be cleansed risk getting beaten by superstitious villagers, who may also harm the woman's children. It is argued that this notion arose from the idea that if a husband dies, the woman may have performed witchcraft against him.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pri.org/stories/2018-10-23/these-kenyan-widows-are-fighting-against-sexual-cleansing|title=These Kenyan widows are fighting against sexual 'cleansing'|publisher=pri.org|accessdate=7 November 2018|date=23 October 2018}}</ref> Widow inheritance (also known as bride inheritance) is a cultural and social practice whereby a widow is required to marry a male relative of her late husband, often his brother.

===Accusations of witchcraft===
[[File:Schiltach Flugblatt.JPG|thumb|left|upright|A 1533 account of the execution of a witch charged with burning the [[Germany|German]] town of [[Schiltach]] in 1531]]
[[Witch trials in the early modern period]] (between the 15th and 18th centuries) were common in Europe and in the European colonies in North America. Today, there remain regions of the world (such as parts of [[Sub-Saharan Africa]], rural [[North India]], and [[Papua New Guinea]]) where belief in [[witchcraft]] is held by many people, and women accused of being witches are subjected to serious violence.<ref>''Citations'':
* {{cite journal | last = Diwan | first = Mohammed A. | title = Conflict between state legal norms and norms underlying popular beliefs: witchcraft in Africa as a case study | journal = [[Duke Journal of Comparative & International Law]] | volume = 14 | issue = 2 | pages = 351&ndash;388 | publisher = [[Duke University School of Law|Duke Law School]] | date = Summer 2004 | url = https://scholarship.law.duke.edu/djcil/vol14/iss2/5/ | ref = harv }} [https://scholarship.law.duke.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?referer=&httpsredir=1&article=1129&context=djcil#H2N1 Pdf.]
* {{cite book |last=Ally |first=Yaseen |title=Witch hunts in modern South Africa: an under-represented facet of gender-based violence (fact sheet) |url=http://www.mrc.ac.za/crime/witchhunts.pdf |publisher=[[South African Medical Research Council]] |date=June 2009 |accessdate=12 December 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425074549/http://www.mrc.ac.za/crime/witchhunts.pdf |archive-date=25 April 2012 |url-status=dead}}
*{{cite news | last=Staff writer | title=Woman burned alive for 'sorcery' in Papua New Guinea | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-21363894 | work=[[BBC News]] | date=7 February 2013 | access-date=12 December 2013 }}</ref> In addition, there are also countries that have criminal legislation against the practice of witchcraft. In [[Saudi Arabia]], witchcraft remains a crime [[punishable by death]].<ref>{{cite web | last = Staff writer |url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/news/saudi-arabia-beheading-sorcery-shocking-2011-12-12 |title=Saudi Arabia: Beheading for 'sorcery' shocking | website = amnesty.org |publisher=[[Amnesty International]] |date=12 December 2011 |accessdate=12 December 2013}}</ref>

===State violence===

====War rape and sexual slavery during military conflict====
[[File:Paul Jamin - Le Brenn et sa part de butin 1893.jpg|thumb|200 px|''[[Brennus (4th century BC)|Brennus]] and His Share of the Spoils'', by [[Paul Jamin]], 1893.]]
[[File:Chinese girl from one of the Japanese Army's 'comfort battalions'.jpg|thumb|200 px|[[Rangoon]], [[Myanmar|Burma]]. 8 August 1945. A young [[Chinese diaspora|ethnic Chinese]] woman from one of the [[Imperial Japanese Army]]'s "comfort battalions" is interviewed by an [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] officer.]]

Militarism produces special environments that allow for increased violence against women. [[War rapes]] have accompanied warfare in virtually every known historical era.<ref>{{cite book | last = Washington | first = Harold C. | chapter = 'Lest he die in battle and another man take her': violence and the construction of gender in the laws of Deuteronomy 20-22 | chapter-url = https://books.google.com/books?id=2rZnXQwPX8gC&pg=PA203 | editor-last1 = Matthews | editor-first1 = Victor H. | editor-last2 = Levinson | editor-first2 = Bernard M. | editor-last3 = Frymer-Kensky | editor-first3 = Tikva  | title = Gender and law in the Hebrew Bible and the ancient Near East | page = 203 | publisher = T & T Clark | location = London New York | year = 2004 | isbn = 9780567080981 }}</ref> Rape in the course of war is mentioned multiple times in the Bible: "For I will gather all the nations against Jerusalem to battle, and the city shall be taken and the houses plundered and the women raped..." {{bibleref|Zechariah|14:2|ESV}} "Their little children will be dashed to death before their eyes. Their homes will be sacked, and their wives will be raped."{{bibleref|Isaiah|13:16|NLT}}

War rapes are rapes committed by soldiers, other combatants or civilians during armed conflict or war, or during military occupation, distinguished from sexual assaults and rape committed amongst troops in military service. It also covers the situation where women are forced into prostitution or [[sexual slavery]] by an occupying power. During World War II the Japanese military established brothels filled with "[[comfort women]]", girls and women who were forced into sexual slavery for soldiers, exploiting women for the purpose of creating access and entitlement for men.<ref>{{cite news|last=Benedict |first=Helen |url=http://www.inthesetimes.com/article/3848/ |title=Why soldiers rape |work=[[In These Times]] |date=14 August 2008 | access-date = 10 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last = Morris-Suzuki | first = Tessa | title = Japan's 'Comfort Women': It's time for the truth (in the ordinary, everyday sense of the word) | journal = Japan Focus (The Asia-Pacific Journal) | volume = 5 | issue = 3 | date = 1 March 2007 | url = http://www.japanfocus.org/-Tessa-Morris_Suzuki/2373  |accessdate=4 August 2011 | ref = harv }}</ref>

Another example of violence against women incited by militarism during war took place in the [[Kaunas Ghetto|Kovno Ghetto]]. Jewish male prisoners had access to (and used) Jewish women forced into camp brothels by the Nazis, who also used them.<ref>{{cite book | last = Dworkin | first = Andrea | author-link = Andrea Dworkin | chapter = Palestinians/prostituted women | chapterurl = https://books.google.com/books?id=Pew3_DPVfnYC&pg=PA316 | editor-last = Dworkin | editor-first = Andrea | editor-link = Andrea Dworkin | title = Scapegoat: the Jews, Israel, and women's liberation | page = 316 | publisher = Free Press | location = New York | year = 2000 | isbn = 9780684836126 }}</ref>

Rape was committed during the [[Bangladesh Liberation War]] by members of the [[Pakistan Armed Forces|Pakistani military]] and the [[militia]]s that supported them. Over a period of nine months, hundreds of thousands of women were raped. [[Susan Brownmiller]], in her report on the [[1971 Bangladesh atrocities|atrocities]], said that girls from the age of eight to grandmothers of seventy-five suffered attacks. {{See also|Rape during the Bangladesh Liberation War}}

Rape used as a weapon of war was practiced during the [[Bosnian War]] where rape was used as a highly systematized instrument of war by Serb armed forces predominantly targeting women and girls of the Bosniak ethnic group for physical and moral destruction. Estimates of the number of women raped during the war range from 50,000 to 60,000; as of 2010 only 12 cases have been prosecuted.<ref>{{cite book | last = UNSC | author-link = United Nations Security Council | title = Report of the International Tribunal for the Prosecution of Persons Responsible for Serious Violations of International Humanitarian Law Committed in the Territory of the Former Yugoslavia Since 1991 | id = A/52/375{{spaces|2}}S/1997/729 | publisher = [[United Nations Security Council]] |url=http://www.icty.org/x/file/About/Reports%20and%20Publications/AnnualReports/annual_report_1997_en.pdf |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120804004034/http://www.icty.org/x/file/About/Reports%20and%20Publications/AnnualReports/annual_report_1997_en.pdf |archivedate=4 August 2012 | date = 18 September 1997 | access-date = 10 November 2012}}</ref> {{See also|Rape during the Bosnian War}}

The 1998 [[International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda]] recognized rape as a war crime. Presiding judge [[Navanethem Pillay]] said in a statement after the verdict: "From time immemorial, rape has been regarded as spoils of war. Now it will be considered a war crime. We want to send out a strong message that rape is no longer a trophy of war."<ref>{{cite book| last = Pillay | first = Navanethem | author-link = Navi Pillay |title=Honorary doctorate acceptance address by Navanethem Pillay, Rhodes University |url=http://www.ru.ac.za/academic/graduation/addresses_and_citations/2005/Judge_Pillay_citation.doc |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060926231120/http://www.ru.ac.za/academic/graduation/addresses_and_citations/2005/Judge_Pillay_citation.doc |archivedate=26 September 2006|date = 2005 |accessdate=27 February 2008}}</ref> {{See also|Rwandan Genocide}}

In 2006, five [[United States Army|U.S. troops]] from a six-man unit [[gang rape]]d and killed a 14-year-old girl in a village near the town of [[Mahmoudiyah, Iraq|Al-Mahmudiyah]], Iraq. After the rape the girl was shot in her head and the lower part of her body, from her stomach down to her feet, was set on fire.<ref>{{cite news | last = Media pool reports |url=http://www.cnn.com/2006/WORLD/meast/08/08/iraq.mahmoudiya/index.html |title=Soldier: 'Death walk' drives troops 'nuts' | work =[[CNN]] | date = 9 August 2006 |accessdate=6 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = US ex-soldier guilty of Iraq rape | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/8039257.stm | work = [[BBC News]] |date=7 May 2009 |accessdate= 10 November 2012}}</ref> {{See also|Mahmudiyah killings}}

A 1995 study of female war veterans found that 90 percent had been sexually harassed. A 2003 survey found that 30 percent of female vets said they were raped in the military and a 2004 study of veterans who were seeking help for post-traumatic stress disorder found that 71 percent of the women said they were sexually assaulted or raped while serving.<ref>{{cite news | last = Benedict | first = Helen | title = The plight of women soldiers |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=103844570 |work=The Nation |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=6 May 2009 |accessdate= 10 November 2012}}</ref>

According to one report, the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]]'s capture of Iraqi cities in June 2014 was accompanied by an upsurge in crimes against women, including kidnap and rape.<ref>''Articles'':
* {{cite news | last1 = Radwan | first1 = Zahra | last2 = Blumenfeld | first2 = Zoe|title=OP-ED: Surging violence against women in Iraq|url=http://www.ipsnews.net/2014/06/op-ed-surging-violence-against-women-in-iraq/|work=[[Inter Press Service]]|date=27 June 2014|accessdate=5 July 2014}}
* {{cite news|last1=Winterton|first1=Clare|title=Why we must act when women in Iraq document rape |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/clare-winterton/why-we-must-act_b_5528162.html|date=25 June 2014|work=[[HuffPost]] |accessdate=10 July 2014}}
* {{cite news | last = Ali | first = Esraa Mohamed | title = Kuwaiti media: "Daash" demands the people of Mosul to provide unmarried to "Jihad marriage"  | url = https://translate.google.co.uk/translate?hl=en&sl=ar&u=http://www.almasryalyoum.com/news/details/466402&prev=search | work = [[Al-Masry Al-Youm|The Egyptian Today]] [Al-Masry Al-Youm] | date = 18 June 2014 |accessdate=10 July 2014}}
:* ''Original Arabic version'': {{cite news|last=إسراء محمد علي|title=إعلامي كويتي: "داعش" يطالب أهالي الموصل بتقديم غير المتزوجات لـ"جهاد النكاح|url=http://www.almasryalyoum.com/news/details/466402|work=المصری الیوم|accessdate=10 July 2014}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'' reported that ISIL's extremist agenda extended to women's bodies and that women living under their control were being captured and raped.<ref>{{cite news|last=Susskind|first=Yifat|title=Under Isis, Iraqi women again face an old nightmare: violence and repression|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/poverty-matters/2014/jul/03/isis-iraqi-women-rape-violence-repression|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=3 July 2014|accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref> Fighters are told that they are free to have sex and rape non-Muslim captive women.<ref>{{cite news|language=sv|title=Det jag har bevittnat i al-Raqqa kommer alltid förfölja mig|url=http://www.dn.se/nyheter/varlden/det-jag-har-bevittnat-i-al-raqqa-kommer-alltid-forfolja-mig/|accessdate=25 September 2014|work=[[Dagens Nyheter]]|date=23 September 2014}}</ref> Yazidi girls in Iraq allegedly [[War rape|raped]] by ISIL fighters committed [[suicide]] by jumping to their death from [[Mount Sinjar]], as described in a witness statement.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ahmed|first=Havidar|title=The Yezidi Exodus, Girls Raped by ISIS Jump to their Death on Mount Shingal|date=14 August 2014|url=http://rudaw.net/english/kurdistan/140820142|publisher=[[Rudaw Media Network]]|accessdate=26 August 2014}}</ref> Haleh Esfandiari from the [[Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars]] has highlighted the abuse of local women by ISIL militants after they have captured an area. "They usually take the older women to a makeshift slave market and try to sell them. The younger girls ... are raped or married off to fighters", she said, adding, "It's based on temporary marriages, and once these fighters have had sex with these young girls, they just pass them on to other fighters."<ref>{{cite news|last1=Brekke|first1=Kira|title=ISIS is attacking women, and nobody is talking about it|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/09/08/isis-attacks-on-women_n_5775106.html?cps=gravity |work=[[HuffPost]] |date=8 September 2014 |accessdate=11 September 2014}}</ref> Describing the [[Yazidi]] women captured by ISIS, [[Nazand Begikhani]] said "[t]hese women have been treated like cattle... They have been subjected to physical and sexual violence, including systematic rape and sex slavery. They've been exposed in markets in Mosul and in Raqqa, Syria, carrying price tags."<ref>{{cite news | last = Watson | first = Ivan | title = 'Treated like cattle': Yazidi women sold, raped, enslaved by ISIS | url = http://www.cnn.com/2014/10/30/world/meast/isis-female-slaves/ | work = [[CNN]] | date = 30 October 2014 | access-date =23 February 2015 }}</ref> In December 2014 the [[Ministry of Human Rights (Iraq)|Iraqi Ministry of Human Rights]] announced that the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] had killed over 150 women and girls in [[Fallujah]] who refused to participate in [[sexual jihad]].<ref>{{cite news|last = NOW News | author-link = NOW News|title=ISIS just executed more than 150 women in Fallujah|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/isis-just-executed-more-than-150-women-in-fallujah-2014-12|work=[[Business Insider]]|date= 17 December 2014 | access-date =23 February 2015}}</ref>

During the [[Rohingya genocide]] (2016 - present) the [[Tatmadaw|Armed Forces of Myanmar]], along with the Myanmar [[Border Guard Police]] and Buddhist militias of [[Rakhine State|Rakhine]], committed widespread gang rapes and other forms of sexual violence against the [[Rohingya people|Rohingya]] Muslim women and girls. A January 2018 study estimated that the military and local Rakhine Buddhists perpetrated gang rapes and other forms of sexual violence against 18,000 Rohingya Muslim women and girls.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Baykan|first=Dildar|date=2 Dec 2019|title=UN official cites horrific crimes against Rohingya|work=Anadolu Agency|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/un-official-cites-horrific-crimes-against-rohingya/1390565#|url-status=live|access-date=12 Nov 2020}}</ref> The [[Human Rights Watch]] stated that the gang rapes and sexual violence were committed as part of the military's ethnic cleansing campaign while the United Nations Special Representative of the Secretary General on Sexual Violence in Conflict Pramila Patten said that the Rohingya women and girls were made the [[Genocidal rape|"systematic" target of rapes and sexual violence because of their ethnic identity and religion]]. Other forms of sexual violence included [[sexual slavery]] in military captivity, forced public nudity, and humiliation.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Quadir|first=Serajul|date=2017-11-12|title=U.N. official says will raise sexual violence against Rohingya with ICC|language=en|work=Reuters|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bangladesh-myanmar-idUSKBN1DC0N7|access-date=2020-11-12}}</ref> Some women and girls were raped to death while others were found traumatised with raw wounds after they had arrived in refugee camps in Bangladesh. Human Rights Watch reported of a 15-year-old girl who was ruthlessly dragged on the ground for over 50 feet and then was raped by 10 Burmese soldiers.<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Bigio|first1=Jamille|last2=Vogelstein|first2=Rachel|title=Analysis {{!}} 5 reasons the U.N. Security Council should care about the Burmese military's sexual assaults on the Rohingya|language=en-US|work=Washington Post|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/monkey-cage/wp/2018/01/03/5-reasons-the-u-n-security-council-should-care-about-the-burmese-militarys-sexual-assaults-on-the-rohingya/|access-date=2020-11-12|issn=0190-8286}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|date=2017-11-16|title=Burmese military 'guilty of widespread rape of Rohingya Muslims'|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/rohingya-crisis-latest-today-burmese-military-rape-accusation-human-rights-watch-muslim-refugees-rakhine-a8057846.html|access-date=2020-11-12|website=The Independent|language=en}}</ref>

{{See also|Rohingya genocide}}

====Forced sterilization and forced abortion====
{{See|Eugenics in the United States|Violence against women in the United States#Forced pregnancy and sterilization}}
[[File:SOU 1929 14 Betänkande med förslag till steriliseringslag s 57 Laughlin.jpg|200px|thumb|right|A map from a 1929 Swedish royal commission report displays the U.S. states that had implemented sterilization legislation by then]]
[[Forced sterilization]] and [[forced abortion]] are forms of gender-based violence.<ref>{{cite web | last = EIGE | author-link = European Institute for Gender Equality |title=What is gender-based violence? |url=http://eige.europa.eu/content/what-is-gender-based-violence | website = eige.europa.eu |publisher=[[European Institute for Gender Equality]] |date=24 August 2015 | access-date = 18 November 2013}}</ref> Forced sterilization has occurred throughout much of the world, both at the hands of the state and from intimate partners. Studies show forced sterilizations often target socially and politically disadvantaged groups such as racial and ethnic minorities, the poor, and indigenous populations.<ref name="Volscho, Thomas W 2010">{{cite journal | last = Volscho | first = Thomas W. | title = Sterilization racism and pan-ethnic disparities of the past decade: the continued encroachment on reproductive rights | journal = [[Wíčazo Ša Review]] | volume = 25 | issue = 1 | pages = 17&ndash;31 | publisher = [[Johns Hopkins University Press]] | jstor = 40891307 | date = Spring 2010 | ref = harv | doi=10.1353/wic.0.0053| s2cid = 159856987 }}</ref> According to the Convention on the Elimination of all forms of Discrimination Against Women, all "women are guaranteed the right to decide freely and responsibly on the number of and spacing of their children, and to have access to information, education, and means to enable them to exercise these rights."<ref>{{cite web |title=Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination against Women |url=http://www.ohchr.org/EN/ProfessionalInterest/Pages/CEDAW.aspx |publisher = [[United Nations General Assembly]] |accessdate=9 May 2016}}</ref>

In the United States, much of the history of forced sterilization is connected to the legacy of eugenics and [[racism in the United States]].<ref name="Volscho, Thomas W 2010" /> Many doctors thought that they were doing the country a service by sterilizing poor, disabled, and/or minority women, whom they considered a drain on the system.<ref name="Volscho, Thomas W 2010"/><ref name="North Carolina Sterilization Program 2011">{{cite news | last1 = Kessel | first1 = Michelle | last2 = Jessica | first2 = Hopper | title = Victims speak out about North Carolina sterilization program, which targeted women, young girls and Blacks | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20111108182852/http://rockcenter.msnbc.msn.com/_news/2011/11/07/8640744-victims-speak-out-about-north-carolina-sterilization-program-which-targeted-women-young-girls-and-blacks | archive-date = 8 November 2011 | url = http://rockcenter.msnbc.msn.com/_news/2011/11/07/8640744-victims-speak-out-about-north-carolina-sterilization-program-which-targeted-women-young-girls-and-blacks | work =[[Rock Center with Brian Williams]] | publisher = [[NBC News]] | date = 7 November 2011 | access-date = 9 May 2016}}</ref> [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]], [[Mexican Americans|Mexican American]], [[African Americans|African American]] and [[Puerto Rican-American]] women were coerced into sterilization programs, with Native Americans and African Americans especially being targeted.<ref name="Volscho, Thomas W 2010" /> Records have shown that Native American girls as young as eleven years-old had [[hysterectomy]] operations performed.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Vincenti Carpio|first=Myla|date=2004|title=The Lost Generation: American Indian Women and Sterilization Abuse|journal=[[Social Justice (journal)|Social Justice]]|volume=31|issue=4|pages=40–53}}</ref>

In Europe, there have been a number of lawsuits and accusations towards the [[Czech Republic]] and [[Slovakia]] of sterilizing Roma women without adequate information and waiting period.<ref>{{Cite book|last=ERRC|title=Coercive and cruel – a report by the European Roma Rights Centre: Sterilisation and its consequences for Romani women in the Czech Republic (1966–2016) |url=http://www.errc.org/cms/upload/file/coercive-and-cruel-28-november-2016.pdf|publisher=European Roma Right Centre| location = Budapest, Hungary|date=November 2016|isbn = 9789638991638}}</ref> In response, both nations have instituted a mandatory seven-day waiting period and written consent. Slovakia has been condemned on the issue of forced sterilization of Roma women several times by the [[European Court for Human Rights]] (see [[V. C. vs. Slovakia]], [[N. B. vs. Slovakia]] and [[I.G. and Others vs. Slovakia]]).

In [[Peru]], in 1995, [[Alberto Fujimori]] launched a family planning initiative that especially targeted poor and indigenous women. In total, over 215,000 women were sterilized, with over 200,000 believed to have been coerced.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Boesten | first = Jelke | title = Free choice or poverty alleviation? Population politics in Peru under Alberto Fujimori | journal = European Review of Latin American and Caribbean Studies  | volume = 82 | issue = 82 | pages = 3&ndash;20 | publisher = Centre for Latin American Research and Documentation | doi = 10.18352/erlacs.9637 | date = 2007 | ref = harv }}</ref> In 2002, Health Minister [[Fernando carbone|Fernando Carbone]] admitted that the government gave misleading information, offered food incentives, and threatened to fine parents if they had additional children. The procedures have also been found to have been negligent, with less than half using proper anesthetic.<ref>{{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = Mass sterilisation scandal shocks Peru | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/2148793.stm | work = [[BBC News]] | date = 24 July 2002 | access-date = 9 May 2016}}</ref>

In China, the [[one child policy]] included forced abortions and forced sterilization.<ref>''Citations'':

* {{cite news|url=http://www.globalpost.com/dispatch/news/regions/asia-pacific/china/130409/china-mother-dies-after-forced-sterilization-one-child-policy|title=China: Mother of 2 dies after forced sterilization|last=Jackson|first=Allison|date=9 April 2013|work=[[GlobalPost]]|access-date=18 November 2013}}
* {{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/news-and-updates/thousands-risk-forced-sterilization-china-2010-04-22|title=Thousands at risk of forced sterilization in China|last=AI|author-link=Amnesty International|date=22 April 2010|publisher=[[Amnesty International]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130529125647/https://www.amnesty.org/en/news-and-updates/thousands-risk-forced-sterilization-china-2010-04-22|archive-date=29 May 2013|access-date=18 November 2013}}
* {{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-china-18435126|title=China forced abortion photo sparks outrage|last=Staff writer|date=14 June 2012|work=[[BBC News]]|access-date=18 November 2013}}
* {{cite book|url=http://www.hrnk.org/uploads/pdfs/HRNK_HiddenGulag2_Web_5-18.pdf|title=The Hidden Gulag|last=Hawk|first=David|date=2012|publisher=The Committee for Human Rights in North Korea|edition=2nd|location=Washington DC|oclc=793983613|access-date=18 November 2013}}</ref> Forced sterilization is also practiced in Uzbekistan.<ref>{{cite news | last = Antelava | first = Natalia | title=Uzbekistan's policy of secretly sterilising women| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-17612550 | work=[[BBC World Service]] | date=12 April 2012| access-date = 18 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media | people = Natalia Antelava (reporter) and Wesley Stephenson (producer) | access-date = 18 November 2013 |date=16 April 2012 | title= Forced sterilisation in Uzbekistan | medium= Audio | minutes = 20:30 | series = [[Crossing Continents]] | publisher= [[BBC Radio 4]] | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01fjx63}}</ref>

====Violence by the police and other authority figures====
[[File:Taliban beating woman in public RAWA.jpg|right|thumb|250px|A member of the Taliban's [[Mutaween#Other groups|religious police]] beating an Afghan woman in [[Kabul]] on 26 August 2001.]]
When police officers misuse their power as agents of the state to physically and [[sexual harassment|sexually harass]] and assault victims, the survivors, including women, feel much less able to report the violence.<ref>{{Cite episode
| title = Covering 'Tainted Justice' and winning a Pulitzer | url = https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=126386819 | series = Fresh Air | serieslink = Fresh Air | credits = Barbara Laker and Wendy Ruderman, hosted by [[Terry Gross]] | network = NPR | station = [[WHYY-FM|WHYY]]| location = Philadelphia | airdate = 3 May 2010 | transcripturl= }}</ref> It is standard procedure for police to force entry into the victim's home even after the victim's numerous requests for them to go away.<ref>{{cite book | last = Suk | first = Jeannie | author-link = Jeannie Suk | title = At home in the law: how the domestic violence revolution is transforming privacy | publisher = Yale University Press | location = New Haven | year = 2009 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=UML8Ke4IpTEC | isbn = 9780300172621 }}</ref> Government agencies often disregard the victim's right to [[Freedom of association#Intimate association|freedom of association]] with their perpetrator.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Hanna | first = Cheryl | title = No right to choose: mandated victim participation in domestic violence prosecutions | journal = [[Harvard Law Review]] | volume = 109 | issue = 8 | pages = 1849&ndash;1910 | publisher = The Harvard Law Review Association | doi = 10.2307/1342079 | jstor = 1342079 | ssrn = 1276830 | date = June 1996 | s2cid = 143393426 | ref = harv }}</ref> [[Women's shelter|Shelter]] workers are often reduced themselves to contributing to violence against women by exploiting their [[vulnerability]] in exchange for a paying job.<ref>{{cite book | last = Koyama | first = Emi | chapter = Disloyal to feminism: Abuse of survivors within the domestic violence shelter system | chapterurl = https://books.google.com/books?id=lZmFjwEACAAJ | editor-last = INCITE! Women of Colour Against Violence | title = Color of violence: the INCITE! anthology | publisher = Duke University Press | location = Durham | year = 2016 | isbn = 9780822373445 | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/colorofviolencei00unse }}</ref>

Human rights violations perpetrated by police and military personnel in many countries are correlated with decreased access to public health services and increased practices of risky behavior among members of vulnerable groups, such as women and female sex workers.<ref name="Beletsky L, Martinex G, Gaines T, et al. 2012 403–410">{{cite journal | last1 = Beletsky | first1 = Leo |display-authors=etal | title = Mexico's northern border conflict: collateral damage to health and human rights of vulnerable groups | journal = [[Pan American Journal of Public Health]] | volume = 31 | issue = 5 | pages = 403&ndash;410 | publisher = [[Pan American Health Organization]] | doi = 10.1590/s1020-49892012000500008 | pmc = 3660986 | pmid = 22767041 | date = May 2012 | ref = harv }}</ref> These practices are especially widespread in settings with a weak rule of law and low levels of police and military management and professionalism. Police abuse in this context has been linked to a wide range of risky behaviors and health outcomes, including post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD), and substance abuse.<ref name="Beletsky L, Martinex G, Gaines T, et al. 2012 403–410"/><ref>''Other citations'':   
* {{cite journal | last1 = Strathdee | first1 = Steffanie A. |display-authors=etal | title = Social and structural factors associated with HIV infection among female sex workers who inject drugs in the Mexico-US border region | journal = [[PLOS One]] | volume = 6 | issue = 4 |page=e19048 | publisher = [[PLOS]] | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0019048 |pmc=3081836 |pmid=21541349 | date = 25 April 2011 | ref = harv | bibcode = 2011PLoSO...619048S }}
* {{cite journal | last1 = Ramos | first1 = Rebeca |display-authors=etal | title = A tale of two cities: social and environmental influences shaping risk factors and protective behaviors in two Mexico-US border cities | journal = [[Health & Place]] | volume = 15 | issue = 4 | pages = 999&ndash;1005 | publisher = [[Elsevier]] | doi = 10.1016/j.healthplace.2009.04.004 | pmid = 19464228 | pmc = 2735581 | date = December 2009 | ref = harv }}
* {{cite journal | last1 = Pollini | first1 = Robin A. |display-authors=etal | title = Syringe possession arrests are associated with receptive syringe sharing in two Mexico-US border cities | journal = [[Addiction (journal)|Addiction]] | volume = 103 | issue = 1 | pages = 101&ndash;108 | publisher = [[Wiley-Blackwell|Wiley]] | doi = 10.1111/j.1360-0443.2007.02051.x | pmid = 18028520 | pmc = 2214830 | date = January 2008 | ref = harv }}
* {{cite journal | last1 = Pollini | first1 = Robin A. |display-authors=etal | title = High prevalence of abscesses and self-treatment among injection drug users in Tijuana, Mexico | journal = [[International Journal of Infectious Diseases]] | volume = 14 | issue = S3 | pages = e117&ndash;e122 | publisher = [[Elsevier]] | doi = 10.1016/j.ijid.2010.02.2238 | pmid = 20381396 | pmc = 2917477 | date = September 2010 | ref = harv }}
* {{cite journal | last1 = Strathdee | first1 = Steffanie A. |display-authors=etal | title = Individual, social, and environmental influences associated with HIV infection among injection drug users in Tijuana, Mexico | journal = [[Journal of Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndromes]] | volume = 47 | issue = 3 | pages = 369&ndash;376 | publisher = [[Lippincott Williams & Wilkins|LWW]] | doi = 10.1097/QAI.0b013e318160d5ae |pmc=2752692 |pmid=18176320 | date = 1 March 2008 | ref = harv }}
* {{cite book | last1 = Raj | first1 = Anita | last2 = Gupta | first2 = Jhumka  | last3 = Silverman | first3 = Jay G. | chapter = Women, migration, conflict and risk for HIV | chapter-url = https://books.google.com/books?id=JhxwNjWzB6gC&pg=PA107 | editor-last1 = Forbes Martin | editor-first1 = Susan | editor-last2 = Tirman | editor-first2 = John | title = Women, migration, and conflict: breaking a deadly cycle | page = 107 | publisher = Springer | location = Dordrecht | year = 2009 | isbn = 9789048128242 }}</ref> Extortion of sexual services and police sexual abuse have been linked to a decrease in condom use and an elevated risk of STI and HIV infections among vulnerable groups.<ref name="Beletsky L, Martinex G, Gaines T, et al. 2012 403–410"/><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Blankenship | first1 = Kim M. | last2 = Koester | first2 = Stephen | title = Criminal law, policing policy, and HIV risk in female street sex workers and injection drug users | journal = [[The Journal of Law, Medicine & Ethics]] | volume = 30 | issue = 4 | pages = 548&ndash;559 | publisher = [[Wiley-Blackwell|Wiley]] | doi = 10.1111/j.1748-720X.2002.tb00425.x | pmid = 12561263 | date = December 2002 | s2cid = 7242766 | ref = harv }}</ref>

====Stoning and flogging====
[[Stoning]], or lapidation, refers to a form of [[capital punishment]] whereby an organized group throws stones at an individual until the person dies. Stoning is a punishment that is included in the laws of several countries, including Iran, Saudi Arabia, Sudan, Pakistan, Yemen, the United Arab Emirates, and some states in Nigeria, as punishment for [[adultery]].<ref>{{cite news | last = Batha | first = Emma | title = FACTBOX: Stoning - where does it happen? | work = [[Thomson Reuters Foundation News]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160125051613/http://news.trust.org//item/20130927165059-w9g0i | archive-date = 25 January 2016 | url = http://news.trust.org//item/20130927165059-w9g0i | publisher = [[Thomson Reuters Foundation]] | date = 29 September 2013 | access-date = 19 November 2013}}</ref> [[Flogging]] or flagellation is the act of methodically beating or whipping the human body. It is a judicial punishment in various countries for specific crimes, including [[sex outside marriage]]. These punishments employed for sexual relations outside marriage, apart from constituting a form of violence in themselves, can also deter victims of [[sexual violence]] from reporting the crime, because the victims may themselves be punished (if they cannot prove their case, if they are deemed to have been in the company of an unrelated male, or if they were unmarried and not virgins at the time of the rape).<ref>{{cite news | last = Lang | first = Olivia | title=Maldives girl to get 100 lashes for pre-marital sex | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-21595814 | work=[[BBC News]] | date=26 February 2013 | access-date = 19 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Jamali |first=Hasan |url=http://www.today.com/id/15836746/ns/today-today_news/t/rape-case-calls-saudi-legal-system-question/#.UolafidedO6 |title=Rape case brings Saudi laws into focus |work=[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today]] |publisher=[[NBC]] |accessdate=19 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6JdMstMvl?url=http://www.today.com/id/15836746/ns/today-today_news/t/rape-case-calls-saudi-legal-system-question/ |archivedate=14 September 2013}}</ref>

===Female genital mutilation===
{{Main|Female genital mutilation}}
[[File:Fgm map.svg|thumb|250px|Map showing the prevalence of FGM in Africa]]
[[File:FGM road sign, Bakau, Gambia, 2005.jpg|thumb|250 px|Anti-[[FGM]] road sign, Bakau, Gambia, 2005]]
Female genital mutilation (FGM) is defined by the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) as "all procedures that involve partial or total removal of the external female genitalia, or other injury to the female genital organs for non-medical reasons".<ref name="WHO FGM">{{cite book | last = WHO | author-link = World Health Organization |title=Female genital mutilation (factsheet) |url=https://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/fs241/en/ |publisher=[[World Health Organization]] |date= June 2000 |accessdate=18 November 2013}}</ref> According to a 2013 UNICEF report, 125 million women and girls in Africa and the Middle East have experienced FGM.<ref name="unicef.org">{{cite book | last = UNICEF | author-link = UNICEF | title = Female Genital Mutilation/Cutting: A statistical overview and exploration of the dynamics of change | url = http://www.unicef.org/media/files/FGCM_Lo_res.pdf | publisher = [[UNICEF]] | date = 22 July 2013 | accessdate = 18 November 2013}}</ref> The WHO states: "The procedure has no health benefits for girls and women" and "Procedures can cause severe bleeding and problems urinating, and later cysts, infections, infertility as well as complications in childbirth increased risk of newborn deaths" and "FGM is recognized internationally as a violation of the human rights of girls and women. It reflects deep-rooted inequality between the sexes, and constitutes an extreme form of discrimination against women."<ref name="WHO FGM"/> According to a UNICEF report, the top rates for FGM are in Somalia (with 98 percent of women affected), Guinea (96 percent), Djibouti (93 percent), Egypt (91 percent), Eritrea (89 percent), Mali (89 percent), Sierra Leone (88 percent), Sudan (88 percent), Gambia (76 percent), Burkina Faso (76 percent), Ethiopia (74 percent), Mauritania (69 percent), Liberia (66 percent), and Guinea-Bissau (50 percent).<ref name="unicef.org"/>

FGM is linked to cultural rites and customs, including traditional practices. It continues to take place in different communities of Africa and the Middle East, including in places where it is banned by national legislation. FGM is defined as a "harmful traditional practice"<ref name="Shell-Duncan">{{cite journal | last = Shell-Duncan | first = Bettina | title = From health to human rights: female genital cutting and the politics of intervention | journal = [[American Anthropologist]] | volume = 110 | issue = 2 | pages = 225&ndash;236 | publisher = [[Wiley-Blackwell|Wiley]] | doi = 10.1111/j.1548-1433.2008.00028.x | date = June 2008 | ref = harv }}</ref> in accordance to the Inter-African Committee.

Due to globalization and immigration, FGM is spreading beyond the borders of Africa and Middle East, to countries such as Australia, Belgium, Canada, France, New Zealand, the U.S., and UK.<ref>{{cite book | last = Nussbaum | first = Martha | author-link = Martha Nussbaum | chapter = Judging other cultures: the case of genital mutilation | chapter-url = https://books.google.com/books?id=43U8DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA120 | editor-last = Nussbaum | editor-first = Martha | editor-link = Martha Nussbaum | title = Sex & social justice | pages = [https://archive.org/details/sexsocialjustice00nuss/page/120 120–121] | publisher = Oxford University Press | location = New York | year = 1999 | isbn = 978-0195110326 | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/sexsocialjustice00nuss/page/120 }}</ref>

Although FGM is today associated with developing countries, this practice was common until the 1970s in parts of the Western world, too. FGM was considered a standard medical procedure in the United States for most of the 19th and 20th centuries.<ref name=":20">{{Cite journal|last1=Webber|first1=Sara|last2=Schonfeld|first2=Toby L.|date=2003-06-27|title=Cutting History, Cutting Culture: Female Circumcision in the United States|url=https://muse.jhu.edu/article/44151|journal=The American Journal of Bioethics|volume=3|issue=2|pages=65–66|issn=1536-0075|doi=10.1162/152651603766436324|pmid=12859826|s2cid=13202773}}</ref> Physicians performed surgeries of varying invasiveness to treat a number of diagnoses, including [[hysteria]], [[Depression (mood)|depression]], [[nymphomania]], and [[frigidity]]. The medicalization of FGM in the United States allowed these practices to continue until the second part of the 20th century, with some procedures covered by [[Blue Cross Blue Shield Association|Blue Cross Blue Shield Insurance]] until 1977.<ref name=":33">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LViJROLfEGQC&q=Watson,+M.+(2005).+Female+circumcision+from+Africa+to+the+Americas:+Slavery+to+the+present.+The+Social+Sciences+Journal,+42,+421-437.&pg=PA106|title=Women in Developing Countries: A Reference Handbook|last=Kinnear|first=Karen L.|date=2011|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=9781598844252|language=en}}</ref><ref name=":20" />

The [[Convention on preventing and combating violence against women and domestic violence|Istanbul Convention]] prohibits female genital mutilation (Article 38).<ref>{{cite book | title = Council of Europe Convention on preventing and combating violence against women and domestic violence | url = https://rm.coe.int/168046031c | date = 12 April 2011 | access-date = 8 October 2017}}</ref>

As of 2016, in [[Africa]], FGM has been legally banned in Benin, Burkina Faso, Central African Republic, Chad, Côte d'Ivoire, Djibouti, Egypt, Eritrea, Ethiopia, Gambia, Ghana, Guinea, Guinea Bissau, Kenya, Mauritania, Niger, Nigeria, Senegal, South Africa, Tanzania, Togo, Uganda, and Zambia.<ref>''Citations'':
* {{cite news | last = Lyons | first = Kate | title = The Gambia bans female genital mutilation | url = https://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/nov/24/the-gambia-bans-female-genital-mutilation | work = [[The Guardian]] | date = 24 November 2015 | access-date = 9 May 2016}}
* {{cite news | last = Richards | first = Kimberly | title = History has been made: female genital mutilation banned in Nigeria | url = http://aplus.com/a/nigeria-bans-genital-mutilation | work = [[A Plus (aplus.com)|A Plus]] | date = 3 June 2015 | access-date = 9 May 2016}}
* {{cite book | last = UNFPA | author-link = UNFPA | title = Female genital mutilation (FGM) frequently asked questions | url = http://www.unfpa.org/resources/female-genital-mutilation-fgm-frequently-asked-questions | publisher = [[United Nations Population Fund]] | date = December 2015 | access-date = 9 May 2016}}</ref>

There exist several approaches that were set up by international health organizations and civil societies (for example, [[Tostan]]) aimed at eliminating the practice of FGM in implemented countries: 
# FGM as a Health issue (also known as health risks approach)
# FGM as a Human Rights issue (also known as Human Rights-based approach)

Some scholars suggests that, when dealing with FGM, it is necessary to take lessons from history, particularly 19th-century campaign against [[foot-binding]] in China,<ref name="Kwame Appiah">{{cite news | last = Appiah | first = Kwame Anthony | author-link = Kwame Anthony Appiah | title = The art of social change | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/24/magazine/24FOB-Footbinding-t.html?pagewanted=all |work = [[The New York Times]] |date=22 October 2010 |accessdate=2 December 2013}}</ref> which was successful.

===Breast ironing===
{{Main|Breast ironing}}
Breast ironing (also known as "breast flattening") is the practice of pounding and massaging the [[breasts]] of a [[puberty|pubescent girl]], using hard or heated objects, in an attempt to try to make them stop developing or disappear.<ref name="west-info.eu">{{cite book | last = Tapscott | first = Rebecca |title=Understanding breast "ironing": a study of the methods, motivations, and outcomes of breast flattening practices in Cameroon | url = http://www.west-info.eu/files/Feinstein-International-Center-Understanding-breast-ironing-a-study-of-the-methods-motivations-and-outcomes-of-breast-flattening-practices-in-Cameroon-20121.pdf | publisher= [[Feinstein International Center]] | date = 14 May 2012 | access-date = 25 January 2014}}</ref><ref name="BBC Cameroon Breast Ironing">{{cite news | last = Sa'ah | first = Randy Joe | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/5107360.stm | work=[[BBC News]] | title=Cameroon girls battle 'breast ironing' | date=23 June 2006 | access-date = 25 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Penney | first = Joe | url= https://widerimage.reuters.com/story/breast-ironing | work=[[Reuters]] |title= Breast ironing | date = 27 January 2014 | access-date = 25 January 2014}}</ref> It is typically carried out by the girl's mother, with the aim of making the girl less sexually attractive to men and boys, so that her virginity is preserved and she can continue her education.<ref name="BBC Cameroon Breast Ironing"/><ref>{{cite book | last = Ngunshi | first = Rosaline | title = Breast ironing: a harmful practice that has been silenced for too long | url = http://www2.ohchr.org/english/bodies/cedaw/docs/cedaw_crc_contributions/GenderEmpowermentandDevelopment.pdf | publisher = Gender Empowerment and Development (GeED) | date = 24 August 2011 }}</ref> It is practiced primarily in [[Cameroon]], but has also been reported across other areas in [[West Africa|West]] and [[Central Africa]].<ref name="west-info.eu"/><ref name="BBC Cameroon Breast Ironing"/><ref>{{cite news| last = Mabuse | first = Nkepile | title = Breast ironing tradition targeted in Cameroon | url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/07/27/cameroon.breast.ironing/ | work=[[CNN]] | date=28 July 2011 | access-date = 25 January 2014}}</ref> Breast ironing is very painful and can have negative emotional and physical consequences.<ref name="west-info.eu"/><ref name="BBC Cameroon Breast Ironing"/>

===Obstetric violence===
{{See|Abuse during childbirth}}
"Obstetric violence" refers to acts categorized as physically or psychologically violent in the context of labor and birth. In most developed and many [[developing countries]], birth takes place in an increasingly medicalized environment; with numerous surgical interventions that the pregnant woman can sometimes be coerced into accepting, or which are done without her consent, or which are unnecessary.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Habek | first1 = Dubravko | last2 = Vuković Bobić | first2 = Mirna | last3 = Hrgović | first3 = Zlatko | title = Possible feto-maternal clinical risk of the Kristeller's expression | journal = [[Central European Journal of Medicine]] | volume = 3 | issue = 2 | pages = 3&ndash;6 | publisher = [[Walter de Gruyter]] | doi = 10.2478/s11536-008-0008-z | date = 2008 | s2cid = 57243548 | ref = harv }}</ref><ref name="WHO_Normal">{{cite book | last = WHO | author-link = World Health Organization | title = Care in normal birth: a practical guide | id = WHO/FRH/MSM/96.24 | url =https://www.who.int/maternal_child_adolescent/documents/who_frh_msm_9624/en/ | publisher = [[World Health Organization]] | location = Geneva, Switzerland | series = Safe Motherhood Practical Guide | year = 1996 | access-date = 2 December 2013}} [http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/63167/1/WHO_FRH_MSM_96.24.pdf Pdf.]
:''Also as'':
:* {{cite journal | last = Technical Working Group, World Health Organization | author-link = World Health Organization | title = Care in normal birth: a practical guide | journal = [[Birth (journal)|Birth]] | volume = 24 | issue = 2 | pages = 121&ndash;123 | publisher = [[Wiley-Blackwell|Wiley]] | doi = 10.1111/j.1523-536X.1997.00121.pp.x | date = June 1997 | ref = harv }}</ref>

Many such practices originate in patriarchal ideologies. The WHO stated: "in normal birth, there should be a valid reason to interfere with the natural process. The aim of care is to achieve a healthy mother and child with the least possible level of intervention compatible with safety."<ref name="doi.org">{{cite journal | last1 = Dobbeleir | first1 = Julie M.L.C.L. | last2 = Landuyt | first2 = Koenraad Van | last3 = Monstrey | first3 = Stan J. | title = Aesthetic surgery of the female genitalia | journal = Seminars in Plastic Surgery | volume = 25 | issue = 2 | pages = 130&ndash;141 | publisher = [[Thieme Medical Publishers|Thieme]] | doi = 10.1055/s-0031-1281482 | pmc = 3312147 | date = May 2011 | ref = harv | pmid=22547970}}</ref><ref name="WHO_Normal" />

The term "obstetric violence" is particularly used in Latin American countries, where the law prohibits such behavior. Such laws exist in several countries, including Argentina, Puerto Rico and Venezuela.<ref>{{cite web | last = WHO | author-link = World Health Organization | title = Sexual and reproductive health: Prevention and elimination of disrespect and abuse during childbirth | url =https://www.who.int/reproductivehealth/topics/maternal_perinatal/statement-childbirth-govnts-support/en/ | website = who.int | publisher = [[World Health Organization]] | year = 2015 | access-date = 21 October 2017}}
:''See also'':
:* {{cite book | last = WHO | author-link = World Health Organization | title = WHO statement: The prevention and elimination of disrespect and abuse during facility-based childbirth | id = WHO/RHR/14.23 | url = http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/134588/1/WHO_RHR_14.23_eng.pdf | publisher = [[World Health Organization]] | location = Geneva, Switzerland | series = Human Reproduction Programme (HRP) | year = 2015}}</ref>

=== Violence against indigenous women ===
Indigenous women around the world are often targets of sexual assault or physical violence. Many indigenous communities are rural, with few resources and little help from the government or non-state actors. These groups also often have strained relationships with law enforcement, making prosecution difficult. Many indigenous societies also find themselves at the center of land disputes between nations and ethnic groups, often resulting in these communities bearing the brunt of national and ethnic conflicts.<ref>{{cite book | last1 = UNFPA | last2 = UNICEF | last3 = UN Women | last4 = ILO | last5 = Office of the Special Representative of the Secretary-General on Violence against Children (OSRSG/VAC) | author-link1 = United Nations Population Fund | author-link2 = UNICEF | author-link3 = UN Women | author-link4 = International Labour Organization | title = Breaking the silence on violence against indigenous girls, adolescents and young women: A call to action based on an overview of existing evidence from Africa, Asia Pacific and Latin America | url = http://www.unfpa.org/resources/breaking-silence-violence-against-indigenous-girls-adolescents-and-young-women | publisher = [[UNICEF]] | date = May 2013 | access-date = 10 May 2016}} [https://www.unfpa.org/sites/default/files/resource-pdf/VAIWG_FINAL.pdf Pdf.]</ref>

Violence against indigenous women is often perpetrated by the state, such as in [[Peru]], in the 1990s. President [[Alberto Fujimori]] (in office from 1990 to 2000) has been accused of [[genocide]] and [[crimes against humanity]] as a result of a [[forced sterilization]] program put in place by his administration.<ref>{{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = Mass sterilization scandal shocks Peru | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/2148793.stm | work = [[BBC News]] | date = 24 July 2002 | access-date = 30 April 2006}}</ref> During his presidency, Fujimori put in place a program of forced sterilizations against indigenous people (mainly the [[Quechua people|Quechuas]] and the [[Aymara people|Aymaras]]), in the name of a "[[public health]] plan", presented 28 July 1995.

[[Domestic violence in Bolivia|Bolivia has the highest rate of domestic violence]] in Latin America.<ref>{{cite news | last1 = Dhillon | first1 = Jaskiran | last2 = Allooloo | first2 = Siku | title = Violence against indigenous women is woven into Canada's history | url = https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/dec/14/violence-indigenous-woman-canada-history-inquiry-racism | work = [[The Guardian]] | date = 14 December 2015 | access-date = 9 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Shiriari | first = Sara | title = Bolivia struggles with gender-based violence | url = http://america.aljazeera.com/articles/2015/4/30/bolivia-struggles-with-gender-based-violence.html | work = [[Al Jazeera America]] | date =  30 April 2015 | access-date = 9 May 2016}}</ref> Indigenous women self-report physical or sexual violence from a current or former partner at rates of twenty-nine percent, in comparison to the national average of twenty four percent.<ref>{{cite report | last = UN | author-link = United Nations |title=Thematic paper on the elimination and responses to violence, exploitation and abuse of indigenous girls, adolescents and young women | url = https://www.un.org/en/ga/president/68/pdf/wcip/IASG%20Thematic%20Paper_%20Violence%20against%20Girls%20and%20Women%20-%20rev1.pdf | publisher = Inter-agency Support Group on Indigenous Peoples' Issues | date = June 2014 | access-date = 9 May 2016}}</ref> Bolivia is largely indigenous in its ethnic demographics, and Quechua, Aymara, and Guarani women have been monumental in the nation's fight against violence against women.<ref>{{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = Bolivian women battle against culture of harassment | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-26446066 | work = [[BBC News]] | date = 12 March 2014 | access-date = 10 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Shahriari | first = Sara | title = Combating violence against women in Bolivia | url = https://pulitzercenter.org/reporting/combating-violence-against-women-bolivia | work = [[Pulitzer Center on Crisis Reporting]] | date = 6 March 2015 | access-date = 10 May 2016}}</ref>

[[Guatemala]]n indigenous women have also faced extensive violence. Throughout over three decades of conflict, [[Maya civilization|Maya]] women and girls have continued to be targeted. The Commission for Historical Clarification found that 88% of women affected by state-sponsored rape and sexual violence against women were indigenous.

The concept of white dominion over indigenous women's bodies has been rooted in American history since the beginning of colonization. The theory of manifest destiny went beyond simple land extension and into the belief that European settlers had the right to exploit Native women's bodies as a method of taming and "humanizing" them.<ref name="Bubar, Roe 2004">{{cite journal | last1 = Roe | first1 = Bubar | last2 = Jumper Thurman | first2 = Pamela | title = Violence against native women | journal = Social Justice | volume = 31 | issue = 4 [98] | pages = 70&ndash;86 | jstor = 29768276 | date = 2004 | url = http://www.socialjusticejournal.org/?product=roe-bubar-and-pamela-jumper-thurman-2 | ref = harv }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last = Ramirez | first = Renya | title = Healing, violence, and Native American women | journal = Social Justice | volume = 31 | issue = 4 [98] | pages = 103&ndash;116 | jstor = 29768279 | date = 2004 | url = http://www.socialjusticejournal.org/?product=renya-ramirez-2 | ref = harv }}</ref>

[[Canada]] has an extensive problem with violence against indigenous women, by both indigenous men and non-aboriginals. "[I]t has been consistently found that Aboriginal women have a higher likelihood of being victimized compared to the rest of the female population."<ref>{{cite book | editor-last = Sinha | editor-first = Maire | title = Measuring violence against women: statistical trends 2006 (85-570-XWE) | page = 19 | publisher = Statistics Canada | location = Ottawa, Ontario | series = Juristat | url = http://www.statcan.gc.ca/pub/85-002-x/2013001/article/11766-eng.pdf | year = 2006 }}
:''Citing'':
:* {{cite book | last = Brennan | first = Shannon | title = Violent victimization of Aboriginal women in the Canadian provinces, 2009  | publisher = Statistics Canada | location = Ottawa, Ontario | series = Juristat | url = https://www.statcan.gc.ca/pub/85-002-x/2011001/article/11439-eng.htm | year = 2011 }} Catalogue no. 85-002.
:* {{cite book | last = Perreault | first = Samuel | title = Violent victimization of Aboriginal women in the Canadian provinces, 2009  | publisher = Statistics Canada | location = Ottawa, Ontario | series = Juristat | url = http://statcan.gc.ca/pub/85-002-x/2011001/article/11415-eng.htm | year = 2011 }} Catalogue no. 85-002.</ref> While Canadian national averages of violence against women are falling, they have remained the same for aboriginal communities throughout the years. The history of [[Canadian Indian residential school system|residential schools]] and economic inequality of indigenous Canadians has resulted in communities facing violence, unemployment, drug use, alcoholism, political corruption, and high rates of suicide.<ref name="Bubar, Roe 2004"/> In addition, there has been clear and admitted racism towards indigenous people by the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]], making victims less likely to report cases of domestic violence.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jackson |first=Kenneth |title=Top Mountie Admits Racism in Ranks towards Indigenous People |work=[[Aboriginal People's Television Network]] |date=9 December 2015 |url=http://aptn.ca/news/2015/12/09/top-mountie-admits-racism-in-ranks-towards-indigenous-people/ | access-date = 9 May 2016}}</ref>

Many of the issues facing indigenous women in Canada have been addressed via the Murdered and Missing Indigenous Women (MMIW) initiatives. Thousands of Native Canadian women have gone missing or been killed in the past 30 years, with little representation or attention from the government. Efforts to make the Canadian public aware of these women's disappearances have mostly been led by Aboriginal communities, who often reached across provinces to support one another. In 2015, prime minister [[Stephen Harper]] commented that the issue of murdered and missing indigenous women was "not high on our radar",<ref>{{cite news | title = Full Text of Peter Mansbridge's interview with Stephen Harper | work = [[CBC News]] | url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/canada-election-2105-full-text-of-peter-mansbridge-s-interview-with-stephen-harper-1.3218399 | date = 7 September 2015 | access-date = 9 May 2016}}</ref> prompting outrage in already frustrated indigenous communities. A few months later, Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]] launched an official inquiry into the Murdered and Missing Indigenous Women.

In the United States, Native American women are more than twice as likely to experience violence than any other demographic.<ref name="Bubar, Roe 2004"/> One in three Native women is sexually assaulted during her life, and 67% of these assaults are perpetrated by non-Natives,<ref name="ncai">{{cite book |title=Policy Insights - Brief Statistics on Violence Against Native Women |date=2013 |publisher=NCAI Policy Research Center |page=4 |url=http://www.ncai.org/attachments/PolicyPaper_tWAjznFslemhAffZgNGzHUqIWMRPkCDjpFtxeKEUVKjubxfpGYK_Policy%20Insights%20Brief_VAWA_020613.pdf |quote= A previously reported statistic that, "Among [American Indian and Alaska Native] victims of rape or sexual assault, 86 percent described the offender as non‐Indian" is accurate according to Perry’s analysis (2004) in American Indians and Crime: A BJS Statistical Profile, 1992-2002. However, Perry’s analysis includes reports by both Native men and women victims of rape or sexual assault. Given this brief’s focus on violence against Native women, we include the updated rate of 67 percent reported by Native women victims of rape or sexual assault indicated in Bachman, et al., (2008).}}</ref><ref name="Bubar, Roe 2004"/><ref>{{cite news | last = Chekuru | first = Kavitha | title = Sexual violence scars Native American Women | url = http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2013/03/201334111633172507.html | work = [[Al Jazeera]] | date = 6 March 2013 | access-date = 9 May 2016}}</ref> with Native Americans constituting 0.7% of U.S. population in 2015.<ref name=ACS>{{cite web|title=ACS Demographic and Housing Estimates – 2011–2015|url=https://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/15_5YR/DP05/0100000US|publisher=U.S. Census Bureau|accessdate=23 December 2019|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213004951/https://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/15_5YR/DP05/0100000US|archive-date=13 February 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref> The disproportionate rate of assault to indigenous women is due to a variety of causes, including but not limited to the historical legal inability of tribes to prosecute on their own on the reservation. The federal Violence Against Women Act was reauthorized in 2013, which for the first time gave tribes jurisdiction to investigate and prosecute felony domestic violence offenses involving Native American and non-Native offenders on the reservation,<ref name="rapidcityjournal">{{cite news |last1=Cook |first1=Andrea J. |title=Tribal leaders urged to apply Violence Against Women Act |url=https://rapidcityjournal.com/news/local/tribal-leaders-urged-to-apply-violence-against-women-act/article_f030d4ad-dbda-53ff-bb72-5816465f78d4.html |accessdate=11 January 2020 |newspaper=Rapid City Journal |date=1 April 2015}}</ref> as 26% of Natives live on reservations.<ref name="calgary">{{cite news |last1=Milke |first1=Mark |title=Increasing number of Aboriginals choose not to live on reserves |url=https://www.fraserinstitute.org/article/increasing-number-aboriginals-choose-not-live-reserves |accessdate=23 December 2019 |work=Calgary Herald and Regina Leader Post|date=12 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last1 = Bachman | first1 = Ronet | last2 = Zaykowski| first2 = Heather | last3 = Kallmyer | first3 = Rachel | last4 = Poteyeva | first4 = Margarita | last5 = Lanier | first5 = Christina | title = Violence against American Indian and Alaska Native women and the criminal justice response: what is known | publisher = [[National Institute of Justice]] | url = https://www.ncjrs.gov/pdffiles1/nij/grants/223691.pdf | date=August 2008 |accessdate=10 May 2016}} {{NCJ|245615}}</ref> In 2019 the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] [[United States House of Representatives|House]] passed H.R. 1585 (Violence Against Women Reauthorization Act of 2019) by a vote of 263–158, which increases tribes' prosecution rights much further. However, in the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[United States Senate|Senate]] its progress has stalled.<ref name="gq">{{cite magazine |last1=Willis |first1=Jay |title=Why Can't the Senate Pass the Violence Against Women Act? |url=https://www.gq.com/story/senate-violence-against-women-act |accessdate=11 January 2020 |magazine=GQ |date=13 December 2019}}</ref>

===Violence against immigrant and refugee women===
Immigrant and refugee women often face violence, both in the private sphere (by partners and other family members) and in the public sphere (by the police and other authorities). These women are often in a vulnerable position: they do not speak the language of the country they are in, they do not know its laws, and sometimes they are in a legal position where they may be deported if they make contact with the authorities. Women who seek protection from armed conflict in their countries of origin often face more violence while travelling to the destination country or when they arrive there.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Freedman | first = Jane | title = Sexual and gender-based violence against refugee women: a hidden aspect of the refugee "crisis" | journal = Reproductive Health Matters | volume = 24 | issue = 47 | pages = 18&ndash;26 | publisher = [[Taylor and Francis]] | doi = 10.1016/j.rhm.2016.05.003 | pmid = 27578335 | date = 2017 | s2cid = 21202414 | ref = harv | url = https://halshs.archives-ouvertes.fr/halshs-01441147/file/Sexual%20and%20gender%20based%20violence%20against%20refugee%20women%20a%20hidden%20aspect%20of%20the%20refugee%20crisis.pdf }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Robbers | first1 = Gianna | last2 = Gunta | first2 = Lazdane | last3 = Dinesh | first3 = Sethi | title = Sexual violence against refugee women on the move to and within Europe | journal = Entre Nous | volume = 84 | pages = 26&ndash;29 | publisher = [[WHO]]/Europe | date = 2016 | url = http://www.euro.who.int/en/health-topics/Life-stages/sexual-and-reproductive-health/publications/entre-nous/entre-nous/together-for-a-better-sexual-and-reproductive-health.-entre-nous-no-84,-2016 | ref = harv }} [http://www.euro.who.int/__data/assets/pdf_file/0017/319301/Entre-Nous-84-full-book.pdf?ua=1 Pdf.]</ref>

===Violence against trans women===
{{See also|Violence against LGBT people}}
[[Trans women]], especially [[women of color]], are at higher risk of experiencing violence than [[cisgender women]].<ref>{{Cite report |url=https://www.apa.org/about/policy/psychological-practice-girls-women.pdf |title=APA Guidelines for Psychological Practice with Girls and Women|year=2018 |author=American Psychological Association|page=11|quote=Transgender women are at a notably higher risk of violence than their cisgender counterparts...especially transgender women of color}}</ref> Trans women commonly experience intimate partner violence, with one study finding that 31.1% of trans people experience it, and another finding that half of all trans women experience it.<ref name="williams">{{Cite journal |last1=Brown |first1=Taylor N.T. |last2=Herman |first2=Jody L. |year=2015 |title=Intimate Partner Violence and Sexual Abuse Among LGBT People: A Review of Existing Research |url=https://williamsinstitute.law.ucla.edu/wp-content/uploads/Intimate-Partner-Violence-and-Sexual-Abuse-among-LGBT-People.pdf |journal=The Williams Institute: UCLA School of Law}}</ref><ref name="lang">{{Cite journal |last=Langenderfer-Magruder |first=Lisa|year=2016 |title=Experiences of Intimate Partner Violence and Subsequent Police Reporting Among Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Transgender, and Queer Adults in Colorado: Comparing Rates of Cisgender and Transgender Victimization |journal=Journal of Interpersonal Violence |volume=31 |issue=5 |pages=855–871 |doi=10.1177/0886260514556767 |issn=1552-6518 |pmid=25392392|s2cid=24880033}}</ref><ref name="risser">{{Cite journal |last=Risser |first=Jan M. H. |date=2005-10-11 |title=Sex, Drugs, Violence, and HIV Status Among Male-to-Female Transgender Persons in Houston, Texas |journal=International Journal of Transgenderism |volume=8 |issue=2–3 |pages=67–74 |doi=10.1300/J485v08n02_07 |s2cid=71399447 |issn=1553-2739}}</ref> Trans women also often face abuse by police, and [[transgender sex workers]] often face violence from clients.<ref name="whotrans">{{Cite web |url=https://www.who.int/hiv/topics/transgender/about/en/ |title=Transgender people |website=World Health Organization |access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref> Trans women who are survivors of violence can have a harder time finding [[domestic violence shelter]]s, as some shelters do not accept them.<ref name="williams" /><ref>{{Cite journal |url=https://scholarship.law.berkeley.edu/californialawreview/vol106/iss5/6 |title=Are Women's Spaces Transgender Spaces? Single-Sex Domestic Violence Shelters, Transgender Inclusion, and the Equal Protection Clause |last=Apsani |first=Rishita |date=2018-10-01 |website=California Law Review |pages=1689 |doi=10.15779/Z38125Q91G |access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref> In 2018, more than two dozen [[transgender]] people were violently killed in the United States, most of them [[women of color]].<ref name="hrc2019">{{Cite web |url=http://www.hrc.org/resources/violence-against-the-transgender-community-in-2019/ |title=Violence Against the Transgender Community in 2019 |website=Human Rights Campaign |language=en}}</ref><ref name="cnn">{{Cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/01/16/health/transgender-deaths-2018/index.html |title=Killings of transgender people in the US saw another high year |last=Christensen |first=Jen |website=CNN |access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref>

===Sport-related===

Sport-related violence against women refers to any physical, sexual, mental acts that are "perpetrated by both male athletes and by male fans or consumers of sport and sporting events, as well as by coaches of female athletes".<ref name="Catherine Palmer">{{cite book|last=Palmer|first=Catherine|title=Violence against women and sport: Literature review|year=2011|publisher=Durham University|location=London|pages=2–5|url=http://www.endviolenceagainstwomen.org.uk/resources/22/violence-against-women-and-sport-a-literature-review-by-dr-catherine-palmer|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106162130/http://www.endviolenceagainstwomen.org.uk/resources/22/violence-against-women-and-sport-a-literature-review-by-dr-catherine-palmer|archivedate=6 November 2014}}</ref>

The documenting reports and literature suggest that there are obvious connections between contemporary sport and violence against women. Such events as the [[2010 World Cup]], the [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] and [[Commonwealth Games]] "have highlighted the connections between sports spectatorship and intimate partner violence, and the need for police, authorities and services to be aware of this when planning sporting events".<ref name="Catherine Palmer" />

Sport-related violence can occur in various contexts and places, including homes, pubs, clubs, hotel rooms, the streets.<ref name="Catherine Palmer" />

====Sport-related violence by male college athletes====

Violence against women is a topic of concern in the United States' collegiate athletic community. From the 2010 UVA lacrosse murder, in which a male athlete was charged guilty with second degree murder of his girlfriend, to the 2004 University of Colorado Football Scandal when players were charged with nine alleged sexual assaults,<ref>{{cite news|last=Vaughan|first=Kevin|title=Colorado woman seeks justice in alleged sexual assault Read more: Colorado woman seeks justice in alleged sexual assault|url=http://www.denverpost.com/firstinthepost/ci_12557039|work=[[The Denver Post]]|date=9 June 2009|accessdate=17 April 2012}}</ref> studies suggest that athletes are at higher risk for committing sexual assault against women than the average student.<ref>{{cite web|last=Brady|first=Jeff|author-link=Jeff Brady (reporter)|title=Scandal Returns to University of Colorado Football|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=105381707|work=[[Weekend Edition]]|publisher=[[NPR]]|accessdate=12 March 2012}}</ref><ref name="chandler1999">{{cite journal|last1=Chandler|first1=Steve B.|last2=Johnson|first2=Dewayne J.|last3=Carroll|first3=Pamela S.|title=Abusive behaviors of college athletes | journal = [[College Student Journal]] | volume = 33 | issue = 4 | pages = 638&ndash;645 | publisher = [[University of South Alabama]] | date = 1 December 1999 | ref = harv |oclc=193500507}}</ref> It is reported that one in three college assaults are committed by athletes.<ref name="johnshopkins1">{{cite journal|last=Mak|first=Stephanie|title=Are athletes more abusive than the rest of the student population?|url=http://web1.johnshopkins.edu/hurj/issue3/spotlight-mak.html|journal=Hopkins Undergraduate Research Journal Online|accessdate=12 March 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229044851/http://web1.johnshopkins.edu/hurj/issue3/spotlight-mak.html|archivedate=29 February 2012|date=2004}}</ref> Surveys suggest that male student athletes who represent 3.3% of the college population, commit 19% of reported sexual assaults and 35% of domestic violence.<ref>{{cite web|last=Staff writer|title=Game stats|publisher=The National Coalition Against Violent Athletes (NCVA)|accessdate=27 December 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161117092517/http://www.ncava.org/statistics.html|archivedate=17 November 2016|url=http://www.ncava.org:80/statistics.html}}
:''Citing'':
:* {{cite journal | last1 = Crosset | first1 = Todd W. | last2 = Benedict | first2 = Jeffrey R. | last3 = McDonald | first3 = Mark A. | title = Male student-athletes and violence against women: a survey of campus judicial affairs offices | journal = [[Journal of Sport & Social Issues]] | volume = 19 | issue = 2 | pages = 126&ndash;140 | publisher = [[Sage Publications|Sage]] | doi = 10.1177/019372395019002002 | date = May 1995 | pmid = 12295457 | s2cid = 146752259 | ref = harv }}
